00:19:13,352 --> 00:19:18,657
Last time, Chef Jong-won had
his first 15-minute cook-off,

474
00:19:18,724 --> 00:19:22,461
<i>and won against Chef Sam,</i>
<i>a veteran in </i>Chef & My Fridge.

475
00:19:22,528 --> 00:19:25,230
He then moved on to challenge
Chef Yeon-bok right away.

476
00:19:25,297 --> 00:19:27,866
It means he wants
to prey on all returning chefs.

477
00:19:27,933 --> 00:19:28,934
TREMBLING

478
00:19:29,001 --> 00:19:30,802
Chef Kang-rok said something like this.

479
00:19:30,869 --> 00:19:33,305
-Yes?
-"Chef Jong-won has gentle and sweet eyes,

480
00:19:33,372 --> 00:19:35,841
-but he's a very scary man."
-I see.

481
00:19:35,908 --> 00:19:38,110
You can't let your guard down
just because he looks nice.

482
00:19:38,177 --> 00:19:40,646
-"He's hiding his claws inside."
-I see.

483
00:19:40,712 --> 00:19:42,548
Chef Kang-rok, did you really say this?

484
00:19:43,115 --> 00:19:45,484
-I mostly study people's eyes.
-Yes, you do.

485
00:19:45,551 --> 00:19:47,486
They're quite functional.

486
00:19:47,553 --> 00:19:50,022
-The eye researcher.
-The eye researcher.

487
00:19:50,088 --> 00:19:52,658
Did you think
Chef Jong-won's eyes were different?

488
00:19:52,724 --> 00:19:56,428
His eyes break like this
and make him look very gentle.

489
00:19:56,495 --> 00:19:59,698
But he made a course meal
during his first battle.

490
00:19:59,765 --> 00:20:00,933
-He did.
-Yes.

491
00:20:00,999 --> 00:20:02,935
-He's bold.
-He has strong nerves.

492
00:20:03,001 --> 00:20:04,069
He has strong nerves,

493
00:20:04,136 --> 00:20:05,537
and there's something about him

494
00:20:05,604 --> 00:20:07,172
-that is unlike his looks.
-I see.

495
00:20:07,239 --> 00:20:08,907
-Don't be fooled.
-No, don't be.

496
00:20:08,974 --> 00:20:11,009
Chef Kang-rok, what about your eyes?

497
00:20:11,076 --> 00:20:12,578
They look dazed.

498
00:20:14,980 --> 00:20:18,917
-Dazed Rok.
-I see. He says his eyes look dazed.

499
00:20:19,618 --> 00:20:22,688
According to the production crew,
Chef Jong-won said this.

500
00:20:22,754 --> 00:20:24,056
"Please call me

501
00:20:24,122 --> 00:20:26,091
the returning chef killer."

502
00:20:27,960 --> 00:20:30,462
HIS KILLER INSTINCT WAS
HIDDEN BEHIND KIND EYES

503
00:20:30,529 --> 00:20:32,698
-He said that himself.
-Yes, he's a scary guy.

504
00:20:32,764 --> 00:20:33,899
The look in his eyes is scary.

505
00:20:33,966 --> 00:20:35,133
You'll be a hit man?

506
00:20:35,200 --> 00:20:36,702
"So don't put me against an easy prey."

507
00:20:36,768 --> 00:20:39,705
"I only want to fight someone
worth my effort when I win."

508
00:20:39,771 --> 00:20:42,074
We found those terms in his contract.

509
00:20:42,140 --> 00:20:44,543
That was why he never talked to me.

510
00:20:44,610 --> 00:20:47,045
-You aren't one of his targets.
-Come on.

511
00:20:47,112 --> 00:20:49,348
-You're invisible to him.
-This is killing my pride.

512
00:20:49,414 --> 00:20:52,451
We'll have to pay compensation
if we put you up against him.

513
00:20:52,517 --> 00:20:53,986
How much of this is true?

514
00:20:54,052 --> 00:20:55,754
Not at all.

515
00:20:55,821 --> 00:20:57,756
Actually, I never said that.

516
00:20:57,823 --> 00:21:01,293
Would you prefer to be
the returning chefs' killer or their prey?

517
00:21:02,094 --> 00:21:03,795
-This is hard.
-It's hard to pick.

518
00:21:03,862 --> 00:21:05,063
One, two, three.

519
00:21:05,130 --> 00:21:06,565
I'll be the killer today.

520
00:21:06,632 --> 00:21:09,101
-I see.
-He has that in him.

521
00:21:09,167 --> 00:21:10,669
HE QUIETLY CONFESSED
HIS TRUE INTENTIONS

522
00:21:10,736 --> 00:21:12,838
I'll show him that
returning chefs are the real killers.

523
00:21:12,904 --> 00:21:14,973
"Returning chefs are the real killers."

524
00:21:15,040 --> 00:21:17,676
-That's right.
-Chef Yeon-bok looks determined today.

525
00:21:17,743 --> 00:21:20,412
I'll show him
how spicy <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> can be.

526
00:21:20,479 --> 00:21:23,015
You have to show him
and put him back in his place.

527
00:21:23,081 --> 00:21:26,985
First of all, will you two use the perks?

528
00:21:27,052 --> 00:21:29,721
If you use it now, the next person can't.

529
00:21:29,788 --> 00:21:33,125
If one of you don't use it,
the next person can.

530
00:21:33,191 --> 00:21:34,893
Chef Yeon-bok, what about the perk?

531
00:21:34,960 --> 00:21:36,762
-I won't use it.
-I see.

532
00:21:36,828 --> 00:21:39,431
-He won't use it.
-He's looking after Poong.

533
00:21:39,498 --> 00:21:40,499
-Yes.
-Thank you.

534
00:21:41,233 --> 00:21:42,701
And Chef Jong-won?

535
00:21:42,768 --> 00:21:44,603
I'll let Chef Kang-rok use it too.

536
00:21:45,237 --> 00:21:46,905
TOUCHED

537
00:21:46,972 --> 00:21:51,009
Both chefs declined to use it
for the next person.

538
00:21:51,076 --> 00:21:54,146
It'd be kind of weird
if Chef Kang-rok took it and used it.

539
00:21:54,212 --> 00:21:56,081
-He's up against Poong.
-Right.

540
00:21:56,148 --> 00:21:57,616
-That's an awkward situation.
-It is.

541
00:21:57,683 --> 00:21:58,684
Thank you.

542
00:21:59,451 --> 00:22:00,552
Thank you.

543
00:22:00,619 --> 00:22:01,720
I'LL TAKE IT

544
00:22:01,787 --> 00:22:04,723
-He'll use it.
-He thanked him.

545
00:22:04,790 --> 00:22:07,592
-He's about to face his demise.
-He is.

546
00:22:07,659 --> 00:22:10,529
He can't afford
to save his face like that.

547
00:22:11,463 --> 00:22:12,998
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS:
PARMESAN, SMOKED BONELESS DRUMSTICKS

548
00:22:13,065 --> 00:22:14,633
SRIRACHA, PARSLEY POWDER, TONIC WATER,
CHILI PEPPER OIL, MAYONNAISE, AND MORE

549
00:22:14,700 --> 00:22:16,702
CHEF YEON-BOK'S INGREDIENTS:
INSTANT CURRY, CURRY POWDER,

550
00:22:16,768 --> 00:22:18,537
CHICKEN POWDER, PORK RIBS, VEGGIE MIX,
OYSTER SAUCE, YUJA PRESERVES, AND MORE

551
00:22:18,603 --> 00:22:20,605
-Chef Yeon-bok, what's your dish?
-Yes?

552
00:22:20,672 --> 00:22:22,808
I'm going to make

553
00:22:23,408 --> 00:22:25,577
Dip It in Curry.

554
00:22:25,644 --> 00:22:27,813
-Dip It in Curry.
-Yes.

555
00:22:27,879 --> 00:22:28,880
Dip It in Curry.

556
00:22:28,947 --> 00:22:32,851
In Japanese cuisine,
there's a dish called <i>tsukemen</i>,

557
00:22:32,918 --> 00:22:35,887
<i>where you dip some noodles in sauce.</i>

558
00:22:35,954 --> 00:22:38,590
It may seem like an unlikely dish,

559
00:22:38,657 --> 00:22:40,659
but when you eat it,
it has a bit of a twist.

560
00:22:40,726 --> 00:22:42,828
And sweet and sour pork ribs.

561
00:22:42,894 --> 00:22:45,997
-It sounds good. Sweet, sour pork ribs.
-Sweet and sour pork ribs?

562
00:22:46,064 --> 00:22:50,402
I'll also make some curry
and let him dip the pork in curry.

563
00:22:50,469 --> 00:22:53,905
It'll be a delicious rendezvous
of two different sauces.

564
00:22:53,972 --> 00:22:55,941
He's using curry.

565
00:22:56,007 --> 00:22:59,111
Up against him is Chef Jong-won.
What's your dish?

566
00:22:59,177 --> 00:23:01,913
Jong-won 84
would like to make this for Bong-sik 84,

567
00:23:01,980 --> 00:23:03,749
so it's called Taco 84.

568
00:23:03,815 --> 00:23:06,852
-Taco 84. What's it like?
-Taco 84.

569
00:23:06,918 --> 00:23:10,555
He left a big impression on me
when he was in <i>Narco-Saints</i>.

570
00:23:10,622 --> 00:23:14,259
So I wanted to make
a South American dish based on that.

571
00:23:14,326 --> 00:23:17,763
He actually had chocolate in his fridge,

572
00:23:17,829 --> 00:23:20,432
so I wanted to make tacos
with chocolate sauce.

573
00:23:21,400 --> 00:23:24,603
-Chocolate sauce?
-Chocolate tacos?

574
00:23:24,669 --> 00:23:25,670
I've never heard of that.

575
00:23:25,737 --> 00:23:27,839
Cacao is grown mostly in South America,

576
00:23:27,906 --> 00:23:30,609
<i>so there's this sauce called mole,</i>
<i>made by blending chocolate,</i>

577
00:23:30,675 --> 00:23:32,310
<i>chili pepper, and garlic.</i>

578
00:23:32,377 --> 00:23:35,113
I'm going to work off that
as I make the dish.

579
00:23:35,180 --> 00:23:37,549
He says he hasn't had chocolate lately
to stay in shape.

580
00:23:37,616 --> 00:23:39,551
-I like it, though.
-He's cutting back on sweets.

581
00:23:39,618 --> 00:23:41,787
-Is that all right?
-Yes.

582
00:23:41,853 --> 00:23:45,690
Their cook-off will begin right now.

583
00:23:45,757 --> 00:23:47,692
Chef Yeon-bok, may I use the microwave?

584
00:23:47,759 --> 00:23:49,528
-What?
-May I use the microwave?

585
00:23:49,594 --> 00:23:51,897
-Yes, sure.
-I have to go back and forth.

586
00:23:51,963 --> 00:23:53,865
-What about that?
-You have it there too.

587
00:23:53,932 --> 00:23:55,700
-I turned the oven on.
-It's used as an oven.

588
00:23:55,767 --> 00:23:57,235
He needs a microwave too.

589
00:23:57,302 --> 00:23:59,070
-He's using an oven and a microwave?
-Yes.

590
00:23:59,137 --> 00:24:04,109
And now, let us begin the round
"A dish with Hyun Bong Sixth Sense twist."

591
00:24:04,176 --> 00:24:07,379
It'd be a twist on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>
for this man to lose.

592
00:24:07,446 --> 00:24:10,315
Chef Lee Yeon-bok is here
to show the Michelin double-star chef

593
00:24:10,382 --> 00:24:12,217
the spiciness of <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

594
00:24:12,284 --> 00:24:14,553
Up against him is Chef Son Jong-won,

595
00:24:14,619 --> 00:24:16,688
who wants double stars
here on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>

596
00:24:16,755 --> 00:24:19,291
and dreams of becoming
the returning chef killer.

597
00:24:19,357 --> 00:24:21,092
Who will become the winner today?

598
00:24:21,159 --> 00:24:24,830
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

599
00:24:24,896 --> 00:24:27,566
THE 15-MINUTE COOK-OFF BEGINS

600
00:24:28,133 --> 00:24:29,868
Gosh, who's going to win this one?

601
00:24:29,935 --> 00:24:32,270
It's a battle between the old powerhouse
and the new powerhouse.

602
00:24:32,337 --> 00:24:34,539
Chef Yeon-bok begins by boiling the pork.

603
00:24:34,606 --> 00:24:36,241
He's boiling the pork first.

604
00:24:36,308 --> 00:24:38,410
He's going to do that
before he fries them.

605
00:24:39,444 --> 00:24:42,614
Will parboiling that before frying
make it more tender?

606
00:24:42,681 --> 00:24:45,917
-It'll cook faster.
-It'll cook faster too.

607
00:24:46,485 --> 00:24:48,653
SON JONG-WON PULLS OUT KITCHEN TOWEL

608
00:24:49,287 --> 00:24:53,658
-The tortilla.
-He said the tortilla was a bit stiff.

609
00:24:53,725 --> 00:24:54,960
He's going to soften them.

610
00:24:55,026 --> 00:24:57,262
I see. Just like that.

611
00:24:58,129 --> 00:25:01,032
He's going to the microwave.
What's he putting in?

612
00:25:01,099 --> 00:25:02,501
The tortilla.

613
00:25:02,567 --> 00:25:03,869
-The tortilla.
-The tortilla.

614
00:25:03,935 --> 00:25:06,037
CHOPPING

615
00:25:06,104 --> 00:25:09,574
Chef Yeon-bok overwhelms his opponent
with the chopping sound.

616
00:25:10,141 --> 00:25:13,345
2. CHOP GREEN ONION, ONION,
THINLY SLICED BEEF LOIN, AND CRUSH GARLIC

617
00:25:13,411 --> 00:25:15,881
Yes, right. Thinly sliced beef loin.

618
00:25:16,448 --> 00:25:17,782
CRUSHING THE GARLIC IN ONE GO

619
00:25:17,849 --> 00:25:21,219
The Chinese cleaver does make a big sound.

620
00:25:21,820 --> 00:25:24,723
SON JONG-WON BEGINS TO CHOP TOO

621
00:25:25,290 --> 00:25:27,058
THROWING OUT THE REMAINS
RIGHT AWAY

622
00:25:28,593 --> 00:25:30,462
Chef Jong-won responds by chopping too.

623
00:25:31,830 --> 00:25:34,966
I thought they didn't make chopping sounds
in Western cuisine.

624
00:25:35,033 --> 00:25:37,202
Isn't that so?
That's the Chinese cuisine style.

625
00:25:37,269 --> 00:25:38,803
There are no such things.

626
00:25:38,870 --> 00:25:40,372
You're saying he did that on purpose?

627
00:25:40,438 --> 00:25:43,742
I believe Western cuisine
doesn't make such loud noises.

628
00:25:43,808 --> 00:25:46,278
Is he trying to pick a fight
with an elder?

629
00:25:46,344 --> 00:25:47,445
He did it on purpose.

630
00:25:47,512 --> 00:25:50,215
GOING BACK TO CHOPPING, MISSES

631
00:25:50,282 --> 00:25:51,616
MISSES

632
00:25:52,117 --> 00:25:54,052
He's doing his best not to make any sound.

633
00:25:54,119 --> 00:25:55,954
EYES SHUT

634
00:25:56,454 --> 00:25:59,291
I've become sensitive to sound.

635
00:25:59,357 --> 00:26:00,358
GROANS

636
00:26:00,425 --> 00:26:02,961
-It must be hard to chop because of you.
-He's trying not to make a sound.

637
00:26:03,028 --> 00:26:05,397
What? I was just sharing my opinion.

638
00:26:05,463 --> 00:26:07,299
-You can make a sound.
-Yes.

639
00:26:07,365 --> 00:26:08,934
-Is that so?
-That was a good blow.

640
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:11,570
I didn't know.
I don't know anything, actually.

641
00:26:11,636 --> 00:26:14,372
-You never cared about that.
-Well, sure.

642
00:26:14,439 --> 00:26:17,642
2. STIR-FRY CHOPPED ONION,
CHILI PEPPER, AND CRUSHED GARLIC

643
00:26:18,209 --> 00:26:22,614
3. OIL PAN, STIR-FRY GREEN ONION,
ONION, BEEF LOIN, GARLIC, AND SOY SAUCE

644
00:26:24,316 --> 00:26:25,684
A FIERY PERFORMANCE

645
00:26:25,750 --> 00:26:27,052
Look at that!

646
00:26:28,219 --> 00:26:30,789
AMAZED

647
00:26:32,057 --> 00:26:34,559
Bong-sik is moved right now.

648
00:26:34,626 --> 00:26:36,061
He looks so happy now.

649
00:26:36,127 --> 00:26:37,295
Do you like that smoky taste?

650
00:26:37,362 --> 00:26:38,897
-Do you?
-I can never have enough.

651
00:26:38,964 --> 00:26:40,865
-He does!
-He can never have enough!

652
00:26:40,932 --> 00:26:43,268
He's starting to use
his usual expressions.

653
00:26:43,335 --> 00:26:45,136
-He can never have enough.
-No.

654
00:26:45,203 --> 00:26:47,138
Look at Chef Yeon-bok's fiery show.

655
00:26:47,205 --> 00:26:48,773
How will he use that stir-fry?

656
00:26:48,840 --> 00:26:51,109
-What's the stir-fry for?
-It's for the curry.

657
00:26:51,176 --> 00:26:52,744
-The curry.
-The curry.

658
00:26:53,545 --> 00:26:56,948
He's making curry now with the broth.

659
00:26:57,015 --> 00:26:58,416
Dip It in Curry.

660
00:26:58,483 --> 00:27:01,086
He's not using just the curry powder.

661
00:27:01,152 --> 00:27:03,288
It already looks delicious.

662
00:27:03,355 --> 00:27:04,489
IT ALREADY LOOKS GOOD

663
00:27:05,790 --> 00:27:07,926
-He's julienning cabbage.
-He is.

664
00:27:07,993 --> 00:27:10,695
Chef Jong-won is
getting the ingredients ready first.

665
00:27:11,262 --> 00:27:13,832
HE THROWS OUT THE REMAINS

666
00:27:14,399 --> 00:27:16,568
4. BOIL WATER, VINEGAR, AND SUGAR
TO MAKE PICKLE JUICE

667
00:27:17,335 --> 00:27:20,038
HIS PET TOWEL HAS RETURNED

668
00:27:20,105 --> 00:27:24,776
5. POUR PICKLE JUICE OVER CHOPPED ONION
AND CABBAGE TO MAKE CABBAGE SLAW

669
00:27:25,910 --> 00:27:28,546
Chef Jong-won is using sriracha sauce.

670
00:27:28,613 --> 00:27:30,181
And peanut butter.

671
00:27:30,248 --> 00:27:33,018
-What's he adding now? Chili oil.
-Chili oil.

672
00:27:34,319 --> 00:27:35,520
TREMBLING

673
00:27:35,587 --> 00:27:38,623
His hand trembled a bit
when he poured lemon juice in.

674
00:27:38,690 --> 00:27:40,291
I guess he gets nervous too.

675
00:27:40,358 --> 00:27:42,727
-He's nervous.
-He must be.

676
00:27:43,294 --> 00:27:44,963
How will you use that sauce?

677
00:27:46,264 --> 00:27:49,401
-I think he's making mole right now.
-Mole?

678
00:27:49,467 --> 00:27:51,569
Are you making mole in secret like a mole?

679
00:27:51,636 --> 00:27:54,072
He's making it in secret
without telling us. Ketchup goes in.

680
00:27:54,139 --> 00:27:55,707
Make it so that even I can understand.

681
00:27:56,841 --> 00:27:59,310
CHEF GOOD VIBES
SHARES HIS INGREDIENT

682
00:27:59,377 --> 00:28:00,679
-Chocolate.
-Chocolate.

683
00:28:00,745 --> 00:28:02,681
-Chocolate.
-That's mole.

684
00:28:02,747 --> 00:28:05,850
Chocolate rarely tastes good in food.

685
00:28:05,917 --> 00:28:09,954
I'm a bit worried because mole is
not very suitable for the Korean palate

686
00:28:10,021 --> 00:28:12,223
-because of the chocolate.
-I see.

687
00:28:13,591 --> 00:28:16,494
Chef Yeon-bok pulls out boiled pork ribs.

688
00:28:16,561 --> 00:28:18,163
-Pork ribs.
-Pork ribs.

689
00:28:18,229 --> 00:28:20,632
-Suk-ku, those are called pork ribs.
-Yes?

690
00:28:20,699 --> 00:28:22,634
I thought it was beef.

691
00:28:23,201 --> 00:28:25,737
SUK-KU IS SUCH A TV PERSONALITY

692
00:28:25,804 --> 00:28:28,206
-That's not the color of beef.
-No.

693
00:28:29,808 --> 00:28:31,476
6. DRY BOILED PORK RIBS,
CUT INTO BITE SIZES AND DEEP-FRY

694
00:28:31,543 --> 00:28:32,544
-He's frying those.
-Yes.

695
00:28:32,610 --> 00:28:35,146
-He's deep-frying pork ribs.
-He's deep-frying pork.

696
00:28:35,213 --> 00:28:38,083
-So you can fry it without batter?
-He didn't even use powder.

697
00:28:38,149 --> 00:28:40,318
-He didn't.
-Not for sweet and sour pork ribs.

698
00:28:42,020 --> 00:28:44,355
He's frying those
without frying powder or batter.

699
00:28:46,725 --> 00:28:48,760
SWOOSH

700
00:28:49,327 --> 00:28:51,763
OPENING UP THE TORTILLA

701
00:28:52,397 --> 00:28:54,632
THE TORTILLA BECAME MOIST

702
00:28:55,200 --> 00:28:57,335
HE USES A CIRCULAR CUTTER
TO MAKE THEM INTO SMALLER CIRCLES

703
00:28:57,402 --> 00:29:01,072
-He cuts them into dumpling skin sizes.
-Will you grill them?

704
00:29:01,139 --> 00:29:03,108
7. TURN TORTILLA INTO CIRCULAR SHAPES
AND OIL THE CUT-OUTS

705
00:29:03,174 --> 00:29:04,609
The tortilla goes into…

706
00:29:04,676 --> 00:29:06,711
-Is that oil?
-Yes, that's oil.

707
00:29:06,778 --> 00:29:08,747
-What's he doing with that?
-Why is he putting it in?

708
00:29:08,813 --> 00:29:10,782
AND NOW,
HE PULLS OUT AN OVEN GRILL

709
00:29:11,449 --> 00:29:13,118
AND HE HANGS
THE TORTILLA PIECES OVER IT?

710
00:29:13,184 --> 00:29:14,586
What's he doing?

711
00:29:14,652 --> 00:29:15,653
What is it?

712
00:29:17,255 --> 00:29:18,389
-What's that?
-What's he doing?

713
00:29:19,190 --> 00:29:21,092
-He's shaping those.
-What is it?

714
00:29:21,159 --> 00:29:23,328
We usually put it over a grill
and cook it in an oven.

715
00:29:23,394 --> 00:29:24,562
HE'LL PUT IT OVER A GRILL
AND COOK IT

716
00:29:24,629 --> 00:29:26,965
Is he doing that to make the taco shape?

717
00:29:27,031 --> 00:29:28,767
That's the American method.

718
00:29:28,833 --> 00:29:30,335
He always uses such techniques.

719
00:29:30,401 --> 00:29:32,570
He uses lots of techniques
we've never seen.

720
00:29:32,637 --> 00:29:35,406
It's like he's laying out laundry
on a drying rack.

721
00:29:35,473 --> 00:29:38,276
-He's such a technician.
-He is.

722
00:29:38,343 --> 00:29:39,944
-He is.
-That's a wonder.

723
00:29:40,011 --> 00:29:42,147
Sam Kim was destroyed
because of such techniques.

724
00:29:42,213 --> 00:29:44,249
Don't let his techniques fool you!

725
00:29:44,315 --> 00:29:47,118
He's showing a new technique
to take Chef Yeon-bok down.

726
00:29:47,185 --> 00:29:50,255
-He's deceiving the fridge owners.
-Exactly!

727
00:29:50,321 --> 00:29:51,756
He's using the oven too.

728
00:29:51,823 --> 00:29:53,958
-He put those in to make taco shells.
-You're right.

729
00:29:54,025 --> 00:29:56,628
Chef Yeon-bok takes a glance.

730
00:29:57,462 --> 00:29:59,864
7. ADD OYSTER SAUCE, SHRIMPS,
AND STARCH WATER TO CURRY AND BOIL

731
00:29:59,931 --> 00:30:02,600
Chef Yeon-bok added shrimps to the curry.

732
00:30:02,667 --> 00:30:04,869
MAKING THE SAUCE
FOR THE SWEET AND SALTY PORK RIBS

733
00:30:04,936 --> 00:30:06,604
I think he's making syrup.

734
00:30:06,671 --> 00:30:10,008
-That's the sauce for the ribs.
-The sauce for the ribs.

735
00:30:10,074 --> 00:30:11,676
He added soy sauce, sugar, and water

736
00:30:11,743 --> 00:30:15,180
-to make sweet and salty soy sauce.
-Sweet and salty sauce.

737
00:30:15,246 --> 00:30:17,248
Sugar, soy sauce, and water.

738
00:30:17,882 --> 00:30:19,551
9. ADD FRIED PORK RIBS
INTO THE SAUCE AND BRAISE

739
00:30:19,617 --> 00:30:22,821
He's adding fried pork ribs
into the sauce and braising them.

740
00:30:25,557 --> 00:30:26,858
He put in a lot of sugar,

741
00:30:26,925 --> 00:30:29,928
so he'll make the soy sauce
coats the pork rib pieces.

742
00:30:29,994 --> 00:30:32,397
It'll work like dredge.

743
00:30:32,463 --> 00:30:34,933
-How does he do this so quickly?
-Right?

744
00:30:34,999 --> 00:30:36,367
The classic, Lee Yeon-bok.

745
00:30:36,434 --> 00:30:38,002
The modern, Son Jong-won.

746
00:30:38,069 --> 00:30:41,272
-Take that into consideration, Bong-sik.
-Okay.

747
00:30:41,339 --> 00:30:44,475
-You have seven minutes.
-Seven minutes.

748
00:30:45,810 --> 00:30:47,846
-Mole.
-That's the mole.

749
00:30:47,912 --> 00:30:51,282
Mole. What's he going to do
by adding that in right now?

750
00:30:51,349 --> 00:30:52,350
-Probably to blend.
-Blending.

751
00:30:52,417 --> 00:30:54,519
Will he blend it in a blender?

752
00:30:54,586 --> 00:30:56,387
Why is he trying to blend the sauce?

753
00:30:56,454 --> 00:31:00,024
<i>Moler</i> means "to grind" in Spanish.

754
00:31:00,091 --> 00:31:01,826
It means "to grind"?

755
00:31:01,893 --> 00:31:05,163
-The chocolate pieces were in lumps.
-The chocolate got lumped?

756
00:31:05,797 --> 00:31:07,265
That's the mole.

757
00:31:07,332 --> 00:31:08,533
It looks good.

758
00:31:09,500 --> 00:31:13,037
He's putting the blended mole
back into the pan.

759
00:31:13,104 --> 00:31:16,207
And he adds some water
to dilute the sauce.

760
00:31:16,274 --> 00:31:18,109
I have no idea what that'll taste like.

761
00:31:18,176 --> 00:31:20,511
I should try that when I check on them.

762
00:31:21,212 --> 00:31:22,413
-What's that?
-Drumsticks.

763
00:31:22,480 --> 00:31:24,649
-Drumsticks.
-Right, the drumsticks.

764
00:31:24,716 --> 00:31:27,285
That already tastes good as is.

765
00:31:27,352 --> 00:31:28,920
It looks good.

766
00:31:28,987 --> 00:31:31,322
Will drumsticks go well with chocolate?

767
00:31:32,390 --> 00:31:35,126
-And the chicken was already seasoned.
-Yes.

768
00:31:35,193 --> 00:31:36,995
Chef Jong-won rarely ever answers us.

769
00:31:39,297 --> 00:31:41,799
-I guess we aren't worth talking to.
-Exactly.

770
00:31:42,634 --> 00:31:44,235
Are we that unworthy to you?

771
00:31:44,302 --> 00:31:45,970
I'M JUST BUSY

772
00:31:46,037 --> 00:31:49,974
And we aren't asking for our sake.
We're asking in the viewer's place.

773
00:31:50,041 --> 00:31:51,743
Let's see how well he does later.

774
00:31:51,809 --> 00:31:54,045
13. MIX MAYONNAISE, WATER, AND
CRUSHED GARLIC TO MAKE GARLIC MAYO

775
00:31:54,112 --> 00:31:55,213
Jeez.

776
00:31:55,847 --> 00:31:58,116
How are you going to use the mayonnaise?

777
00:31:58,182 --> 00:32:01,486
-Tacos are usually served with sour cream.
-Sour cream.

778
00:32:01,552 --> 00:32:03,187
So I'll dilute the mayonnaise

779
00:32:03,254 --> 00:32:05,523
to make it seem like sour cream.

780
00:32:05,590 --> 00:32:07,926
He's using mayonnaise to do that?

781
00:32:07,992 --> 00:32:10,361
-Sung-ju, we only have five minutes.
-Yes?

782
00:32:10,428 --> 00:32:12,764
-Already?
-Yes, you need to go!

783
00:32:12,830 --> 00:32:14,532
You have five minutes, Chef Jong-won.

784
00:32:14,599 --> 00:32:18,102
I'm here at this historical battle
to report on the status.

785
00:32:18,169 --> 00:32:20,071
The classical Lee Yeon-bok

786
00:32:20,138 --> 00:32:21,673
versus the new powerhouse, Son Jong-won.

787
00:32:21,739 --> 00:32:24,208
Look at how he cleans up after himself.

788
00:32:24,275 --> 00:32:25,510
He cleaned up everything.

789
00:32:25,576 --> 00:32:28,680
First of all, this thing.
I was curious about this.

790
00:32:28,746 --> 00:32:31,416
Mole, a sauce made with chocolate.

791
00:32:31,482 --> 00:32:34,185
Let me have a taste of this sauce.

792
00:32:34,252 --> 00:32:35,420
I wonder what it's like.

793
00:32:38,423 --> 00:32:42,860
Does it feel like South America?

794
00:32:44,896 --> 00:32:48,933
Gosh, this doesn't work for me.

795
00:32:49,434 --> 00:32:51,336
-It's a tough one.
-Is it tough to understand?

796
00:32:51,402 --> 00:32:53,271
It's a bit salty.
I think you need more water.

797
00:32:53,338 --> 00:32:56,874
-The hosts are rather accurate.
-I am.

798
00:32:56,941 --> 00:32:59,444
I have a pretty good taste.
Give it a taste.

799
00:32:59,510 --> 00:33:01,612
It's too salty. Is that okay?

800
00:33:01,679 --> 00:33:03,147
I'll add some lemon juice.

801
00:33:03,214 --> 00:33:04,415
It must've been too salty.

802
00:33:04,482 --> 00:33:08,186
It's not that sweet. It only tastes salty.

803
00:33:08,252 --> 00:33:13,358
And Chef Yeon-bok's dish.
Let me taste this sauce too.

804
00:33:13,424 --> 00:33:15,860
-He put in <i>yuja</i> preserves.
-He used <i>yuja</i> preserves?

805
00:33:15,927 --> 00:33:17,395
It just went in at the end.

806
00:33:17,462 --> 00:33:20,631
I added a bit at the end
for subtle flavor.

807
00:33:20,698 --> 00:33:21,766
Otherwise, it'll be all gone.

808
00:33:21,833 --> 00:33:24,202
-Is it done? Does it look good?
-Yes, it's been braised well.

809
00:33:24,268 --> 00:33:25,436
Lee Yeon-bok's sauce.

810
00:33:25,503 --> 00:33:27,205
TASTING THE SAUCE

811
00:33:27,271 --> 00:33:32,477
Is that the taste
that can take down Mr. Double Stars?

812
00:33:33,044 --> 00:33:34,045
TASTING

813
00:33:34,112 --> 00:33:36,114
-Wait.
-Is it too hot?

814
00:33:36,180 --> 00:33:38,216
Wait, did you put in sugar?

815
00:33:38,282 --> 00:33:40,084
I did. It's sweet and sour pork.

816
00:33:40,151 --> 00:33:42,754
-I almost burned my tongue!
-You did?

817
00:33:42,820 --> 00:33:44,589
You should've told me!

818
00:33:44,655 --> 00:33:47,425
Why should he?
It obviously looks scorching hot.

819
00:33:48,226 --> 00:33:51,829
-It's sweet.
-Is it?

820
00:33:51,896 --> 00:33:54,198
It's sweet. The sugar could get too sweet,

821
00:33:54,265 --> 00:33:56,267
but the <i>yuja</i> preserves did the trick.

822
00:33:56,334 --> 00:33:57,702
It adds the sourness.

823
00:33:57,769 --> 00:34:00,772
That's why he's a seasoned chef.

824
00:34:01,272 --> 00:34:03,274
ONCE AGAIN, CLEANING THE BOARD

825
00:34:03,841 --> 00:34:05,510
THIS TIME, HE LAYS OUT PAPER

826
00:34:05,576 --> 00:34:07,478
AND A RULER?

827
00:34:08,179 --> 00:34:09,180
What's that?

828
00:34:09,247 --> 00:34:11,282
HE DRAWS A LINE WITH THE RULER

829
00:34:11,349 --> 00:34:12,850
THE DOUBLE-STAR TECHNICIAN
EVEN DOES ORIGAMI

830
00:34:12,917 --> 00:34:14,085
What's he doing now?

831
00:34:15,086 --> 00:34:18,022
HOW WILL HE USE THOSE?

832
00:34:18,089 --> 00:34:19,857
You have 2 minutes and 15 seconds.

833
00:34:19,924 --> 00:34:20,992
Goodness gracious.

834
00:34:22,560 --> 00:34:25,430
He's using lemon juice. What's that?

835
00:34:25,496 --> 00:34:26,764
-He's doing something.
-Cocktail?

836
00:34:26,831 --> 00:34:29,100
-Cocktail?
-Cocktail?

837
00:34:29,167 --> 00:34:30,735
Will he shake that?

838
00:34:30,802 --> 00:34:32,503
He's making a cocktail.

839
00:34:32,570 --> 00:34:34,405
THAT'S NEW

840
00:34:34,472 --> 00:34:36,507
-A cocktail.
-In South American style.

841
00:34:36,574 --> 00:34:39,243
-But Bong-sik doesn't like alcohol.
-Exactly.

842
00:34:39,310 --> 00:34:41,179
I'm making a perilla leaf cocktail.

843
00:34:41,245 --> 00:34:43,981
-Perilla leaf cocktail?
-Perilla leaf cocktail?

844
00:34:44,048 --> 00:34:45,950
Did you put alcohol in?

845
00:34:46,017 --> 00:34:48,219
-No.
-A nonalcoholic cocktail.

846
00:34:48,286 --> 00:34:50,988
And that's the curry sauce.

847
00:34:51,055 --> 00:34:52,990
There are lots of ingredients here.

848
00:34:53,057 --> 00:34:56,060
-Let me taste the curry.
-Curry and…

849
00:34:56,127 --> 00:34:57,995
-It'll taste strong.
-It will.

850
00:34:58,062 --> 00:35:00,631
-Strong taste and strong taste.
-They're both strong.

851
00:35:00,698 --> 00:35:04,001
-How's the curry?
-They're both strong.

852
00:35:05,870 --> 00:35:07,939
It tastes a bit too weak.

853
00:35:08,005 --> 00:35:11,342
I think that's the right call
to keep it in balance.

854
00:35:11,409 --> 00:35:13,177
-It's a bit bland.
-Is it?

855
00:35:13,244 --> 00:35:14,912
The two sauces will come together,

856
00:35:14,979 --> 00:35:17,248
so it'll be too strong
if the curry was strong too.

857
00:35:17,815 --> 00:35:20,151
-You're getting a huge portion.
-My mouth is watering.

858
00:35:20,885 --> 00:35:23,621
HE FINALLY PULLS
THE TORTILLA OUT OF THE OVEN

859
00:35:23,688 --> 00:35:26,324
And now, the tacos.

860
00:35:26,390 --> 00:35:28,659
Does he have the taco shells?

861
00:35:28,726 --> 00:35:30,661
-You have a minute now.
-A minute.

862
00:35:30,728 --> 00:35:33,998
-We're now under a minute.
-You have only a minute.

863
00:35:34,065 --> 00:35:35,233
Do the shells look okay?

864
00:35:35,299 --> 00:35:36,767
-They do.
-They do!

865
00:35:36,834 --> 00:35:38,736
The shells look fine.

866
00:35:38,803 --> 00:35:43,207
He has four taco shells.
Look at how they're shaped.

867
00:35:43,908 --> 00:35:46,177
LEE YEON-BOK FINISHES UP

868
00:35:46,777 --> 00:35:50,281
You have about 40-something seconds left.

869
00:35:50,348 --> 00:35:53,851
Chef Yeon-bok is done!

870
00:35:53,918 --> 00:35:55,753
Chef Yeon-bok finishes first.

871
00:35:55,820 --> 00:35:59,657
Chef Jong-won follows.
He looks rather anxious.

872
00:35:59,724 --> 00:36:02,093
He's looking at the clock!

873
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:05,596
-The sour cream.
-Thirty seconds!

874
00:36:05,663 --> 00:36:07,698
You have under 30 seconds!

875
00:36:07,765 --> 00:36:10,601
-Oh, no. No!
-You must finish up!

876
00:36:10,668 --> 00:36:12,203
The cabbage.

877
00:36:12,270 --> 00:36:15,306
You're topping it off with the cabbage.
It's the topping.

878
00:36:15,373 --> 00:36:17,041
Where are you going now?

879
00:36:18,676 --> 00:36:20,511
He gets ready to present it.

880
00:36:20,578 --> 00:36:22,180
-Fifteen seconds!
-Oh, jeez.

881
00:36:22,246 --> 00:36:24,382
-He's putting something on it.
-Parsley.

882
00:36:24,448 --> 00:36:26,284
That's parsley.

883
00:36:26,350 --> 00:36:27,718
-Nine!
-Nine!

884
00:36:27,785 --> 00:36:29,954
-That's parsley.
-Nine!

885
00:36:30,021 --> 00:36:31,556
Oh, no. Hurry.

886
00:36:31,622 --> 00:36:33,558
-Seven!
-Seven!

887
00:36:33,624 --> 00:36:36,294
-Six! Five! Four!
-No!

888
00:36:36,360 --> 00:36:38,996
-Six! Five! Four!
-Six! Five! Four!

889
00:36:39,063 --> 00:36:40,464
-Three! Two!
-Three! Two!

890
00:36:40,531 --> 00:36:41,866
He's done!

891
00:36:41,933 --> 00:36:43,501
Two! He's done!

892
00:36:43,568 --> 00:36:45,269
AMAZED

893
00:36:45,336 --> 00:36:46,804
He was good despite my interruption.

894
00:36:46,871 --> 00:36:48,839
His hands trembled a lot at the end.

895
00:36:49,407 --> 00:36:51,342
THE MOST SEVERE HAND TREMORS

896
00:36:51,409 --> 00:36:54,212
It already smells good.

897
00:36:54,278 --> 00:36:57,081
-It's getting hot in here.
-It is.

898
00:36:57,648 --> 00:36:59,817
Gosh, my hands are really trembling.

899
00:37:00,785 --> 00:37:02,920
Be careful.

900
00:37:04,121 --> 00:37:06,224
Be careful. Goodness.

901
00:37:06,290 --> 00:37:07,925
Get in there.

902
00:37:09,393 --> 00:37:12,863
I've never been so distracted in my life.

903
00:37:12,930 --> 00:37:14,865
It was the first time
since my college entrance exam.

904
00:37:14,932 --> 00:37:18,436
Were you distracted? He was.

905
00:37:18,502 --> 00:37:20,938
The two dishes are ready.

906
00:37:21,005 --> 00:37:23,107
-It looks awesome.
-It looks insane.

907
00:37:23,808 --> 00:37:25,176
ANOTHER INSTAGRAM POST
COMING SOON

908
00:37:25,243 --> 00:37:27,411
It looks so shiny.

909
00:37:27,478 --> 00:37:32,049
And now, the chefs finished cooking
these dishes for Bong-sik.

910
00:37:32,116 --> 00:37:34,418
All these ingredients were
the ones I used.

911
00:37:34,485 --> 00:37:37,888
I'm dying to know
because they've changed so much.

912
00:37:37,955 --> 00:37:40,691
-Please try Dip It in Curry first.
-Yes.

913
00:37:40,758 --> 00:37:42,627
DIP SWEET AND SALTY PORK RIBS

914
00:37:44,262 --> 00:37:47,465
INTO SMOKY CURRY!

915
00:37:48,532 --> 00:37:52,436
CHEF LEE YEON-BOK'S
DIP IT IN CURRY

916
00:37:52,503 --> 00:37:53,504
How should he eat that?

917
00:37:53,571 --> 00:37:57,174
You can taste each one by itself,
then dip it in curry after.

918
00:37:57,241 --> 00:37:59,343
I wonder how it'll be
when he dips it in curry.

919
00:37:59,410 --> 00:38:03,047
This was the mix of two sauces
he talked about.

920
00:38:03,114 --> 00:38:04,115
Sweet and sour pork ribs.

921
00:38:04,949 --> 00:38:08,519
Gosh, it must be so smoky.
I can smell it all the way here.

922
00:38:09,320 --> 00:38:11,455
TAKING A BITE

923
00:38:12,390 --> 00:38:14,992
HE SAVORS THE SWEET
AND SOUR PORK RIBS

924
00:38:16,327 --> 00:38:17,728
GULPING

925
00:38:17,795 --> 00:38:20,264
Is the pork rib too tough to eat?

926
00:38:23,067 --> 00:38:25,202
WAIT

927
00:38:26,103 --> 00:38:29,540
WHAT? IS THERE A PROBLEM?

928
00:38:30,708 --> 00:38:33,311
WHAT'S SWEET AND SOUR
PORK RIB LIKE?

929
00:38:33,377 --> 00:38:34,445
Gosh.

930
00:38:34,512 --> 00:38:35,680
I see.

931
00:38:36,480 --> 00:38:38,349
ASTONISHED

932
00:38:38,416 --> 00:38:39,817
He chuckled in astonishment.

933
00:38:39,884 --> 00:38:42,420
RELIEVED

934
00:38:42,987 --> 00:38:45,323
People rarely laugh when they judge.

935
00:38:45,389 --> 00:38:47,358
-I wonder what it's like.
-Yes.

936
00:38:47,425 --> 00:38:50,361
It has a hint
of the usual sweet and sour sauce,

937
00:38:50,428 --> 00:38:52,630
but it's something I've never had before.

938
00:38:52,697 --> 00:38:53,864
A GARLIC CLOVE

939
00:38:53,931 --> 00:38:55,666
He tries the garlic clove too.

940
00:38:55,733 --> 00:38:58,169
-Sung-ju said it was a bit too sweet.
-Yes, the sauce.

941
00:38:58,235 --> 00:38:59,637
-Is it not too sweet?
-No.

942
00:38:59,704 --> 00:39:00,738
It's not.

943
00:39:00,805 --> 00:39:02,773
Try just the curry too.

944
00:39:02,840 --> 00:39:04,642
-Try that first, then together.
-Yes.

945
00:39:04,709 --> 00:39:06,210
You said it was too bland.

946
00:39:06,277 --> 00:39:08,979
It was too bland for my taste.

947
00:39:09,980 --> 00:39:11,549
-This was bland?
-Yes.

948
00:39:13,284 --> 00:39:14,552
Was I wrong?

949
00:39:14,618 --> 00:39:17,388
-I think you tasted it the wrong way.
-Did I really?

950
00:39:17,455 --> 00:39:19,790
I want to put rice in right away.

951
00:39:21,459 --> 00:39:23,327
He wanted to put rice in.

952
00:39:23,394 --> 00:39:26,564
And this is the shrimp I always eat.

953
00:39:26,630 --> 00:39:28,265
Yes, right. The shrimps from Suriname.

954
00:39:28,332 --> 00:39:29,934
The shrimps he enjoys a lot.

955
00:39:30,634 --> 00:39:32,970
-This is so good.
-He says it's so good.

956
00:39:33,037 --> 00:39:35,306
-And now, dip it in curry.
-Yes.

957
00:39:35,373 --> 00:39:38,809
The flavor will change
when you add the two sauces.

958
00:39:38,876 --> 00:39:40,644
It could either taste amazing

959
00:39:40,711 --> 00:39:43,447
or backfire on the original evaluation.

960
00:39:43,514 --> 00:39:45,149
-Dip It in Curry.
-Yes.

961
00:39:45,216 --> 00:39:48,319
You never think about dipping that
into curry.

962
00:39:48,386 --> 00:39:50,788
No, people eat those separately.

963
00:39:50,855 --> 00:39:52,089
How is the mix?

964
00:39:52,923 --> 00:39:54,558
-Gosh.
-What is it?

965
00:39:54,625 --> 00:39:55,926
Why isn't this for sale?

966
00:39:57,928 --> 00:40:00,765
-Well, the ingredients are limited.
-My mouth is watering.

967
00:40:00,831 --> 00:40:04,168
It's not too sweet.
It's seasoned perfectly.

968
00:40:04,235 --> 00:40:06,771
This is sauce, and this is another sauce.

969
00:40:06,837 --> 00:40:08,439
But they mix together so well.

970
00:40:08,506 --> 00:40:12,476
I see. He continues to eat more and more.

971
00:40:12,543 --> 00:40:15,479
I shouldn't make myself full,
but I can't stop myself.

972
00:40:15,980 --> 00:40:20,117
The meat piece he picks up
becomes larger and larger.

973
00:40:20,184 --> 00:40:22,319
-That's turning cold.
-Yes.

974
00:40:22,386 --> 00:40:25,723
Have you forgotten?
Chef Jong-won looks very nervous.

975
00:40:25,790 --> 00:40:27,892
That's the frozen shrimp I eat,

976
00:40:27,958 --> 00:40:30,327
and I buy these pork ribs often too.

977
00:40:30,394 --> 00:40:32,563
Everything I've made seems in vain.

978
00:40:34,198 --> 00:40:36,500
The flavor wasn't something I knew.

979
00:40:37,034 --> 00:40:40,938
This time, you'll try Taco 84.

980
00:40:41,005 --> 00:40:43,040
TACO MEETS CHOCOLATE SAUCE

981
00:40:43,607 --> 00:40:46,444
WITH COCKTAIL FULL
OF PERILLA LEAF FLAVOR

982
00:40:47,178 --> 00:40:51,649
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S TACO 84

983
00:40:51,715 --> 00:40:55,186
He's rinsing out his mouth
to evaluate more accurately.

984
00:40:55,252 --> 00:40:57,788
You can have a bite of the taco first,

985
00:40:57,855 --> 00:41:01,158
then gulp it down with the cocktail
when you feel thirsty.

986
00:41:01,225 --> 00:41:03,327
Is the twist in the cocktail?

987
00:41:03,394 --> 00:41:05,429
Right? There must be a twist.

988
00:41:06,130 --> 00:41:08,065
I wonder what that's like.

989
00:41:08,132 --> 00:41:09,867
TAKING A BIG BITE

990
00:41:09,934 --> 00:41:11,035
The texture must be nice.

991
00:41:11,101 --> 00:41:14,805
He'd make a good food show judge.

992
00:41:14,872 --> 00:41:15,873
It suits him so well.

993
00:41:15,940 --> 00:41:17,908
I can't tell what he's thinking.

994
00:41:17,975 --> 00:41:20,811
-He can play a role like this one.
-Yes.

995
00:41:20,878 --> 00:41:22,913
He's like a food columnist.

996
00:41:22,980 --> 00:41:26,484
He seems like a food specialist.

997
00:41:26,550 --> 00:41:28,752
He's here to give him the Michelin star.

998
00:41:30,988 --> 00:41:32,223
He nods.

999
00:41:34,291 --> 00:41:35,426
GIGGLING

1000
00:41:36,694 --> 00:41:38,596
THE FLAVORS EXPLODE IN HIS MOUTH

1001
00:41:38,662 --> 00:41:39,930
It must be that good.

1002
00:41:40,731 --> 00:41:44,368
DID THE FLAVOR MAKE HIM GIGGLE?

1003
00:41:45,236 --> 00:41:47,171
The spiciness hit me a little.

1004
00:41:47,238 --> 00:41:50,040
I'm probably sweating a little.

1005
00:41:50,107 --> 00:41:52,042
You should try the mojito now.

1006
00:41:52,109 --> 00:41:53,177
The perilla leaf cocktail.

1007
00:41:53,244 --> 00:41:55,012
AND THE PERILLA LEAF COCKTAIL
GOES IN!

1008
00:41:57,915 --> 00:41:59,216
My gosh.

1009
00:41:59,283 --> 00:42:00,584
A REFRESHING FINISH

1010
00:42:00,651 --> 00:42:03,087
-Was there a twist?
-He's going wild.

1011
00:42:03,153 --> 00:42:04,889
Was it different from what you expected?

1012
00:42:04,955 --> 00:42:07,892
The spiciness hits me first,
then the sauce comes.

1013
00:42:07,958 --> 00:42:10,761
-The sour cream.
-The sour cream.

1014
00:42:10,828 --> 00:42:14,164
It covers the spiciness later on.

1015
00:42:14,231 --> 00:42:19,436
Then once I had a sip of that,
I felt refreshed from everything.

1016
00:42:19,503 --> 00:42:21,639
I'm sweating right away.

1017
00:42:21,705 --> 00:42:24,375
That was the twist.
You didn't expect it to be spicy.

1018
00:42:24,942 --> 00:42:26,710
But it's savory and spicy.

1019
00:42:26,777 --> 00:42:28,178
It's savory and spicy.

1020
00:42:28,245 --> 00:42:29,246
That's what's important.

1021
00:42:29,313 --> 00:42:31,081
HE HAS ANOTHER BITE
OF THE TACO WITH A TWIST

1022
00:42:31,148 --> 00:42:33,117
-You'll be sweaty after this.
-I'm curious.

1023
00:42:34,552 --> 00:42:35,686
Gosh.

1024
00:42:36,420 --> 00:42:40,124
He's starting to sweat
from the back of his neck.

1025
00:42:40,190 --> 00:42:41,458
It's hitting me.

1026
00:42:41,525 --> 00:42:43,327
-You should take off your jacket.
-Yes.

1027
00:42:43,394 --> 00:42:47,665
But he put that on to look like
he was born in the year 1984.

1028
00:42:47,731 --> 00:42:48,866
<i>The cover on the outside.</i>

1029
00:42:48,933 --> 00:42:51,235
<i>-The cover? The taco.</i>
<i>-The taco shells.</i>

1030
00:42:51,302 --> 00:42:52,836
<i>It was both crunchy and soft.</i>

1031
00:42:52,903 --> 00:42:55,573
I usually use the tortilla
to make pizza at home,

1032
00:42:55,639 --> 00:42:57,608
and it always came out hard.

1033
00:42:57,675 --> 00:43:00,411
Is there a secret
to making this crunchy taco?

1034
00:43:00,477 --> 00:43:02,279
I made it healthy
by grilling those in the oven.

1035
00:43:02,346 --> 00:43:06,417
<i>I microwaved it first to make it soft,</i>

1036
00:43:06,483 --> 00:43:08,485
<i>-put it in oil, and then grilled it.</i>
<i>-He steamed it first.</i>

1037
00:43:08,552 --> 00:43:09,820
<i>That was delicate.</i>

1038
00:43:09,887 --> 00:43:11,488
You put chocolate in there.

1039
00:43:11,555 --> 00:43:14,224
The chocolate won't taste like chocolate.

1040
00:43:14,291 --> 00:43:17,795
It'll add that subtle bitterness
toward the end of the flavor.

1041
00:43:17,861 --> 00:43:19,830
-Gosh.
-All right, then.

1042
00:43:19,897 --> 00:43:22,866
First, Chef Yeon-bok's Dip It in Curry.

1043
00:43:25,603 --> 00:43:26,870
Yes.

1044
00:43:26,937 --> 00:43:28,439
I'll try the curry first.

1045
00:43:28,505 --> 00:43:31,108
The curry doesn't taste too bland.

1046
00:43:33,277 --> 00:43:35,145
The sauce became richer in flavor.

1047
00:43:35,212 --> 00:43:38,616
-It tastes different from before.
-It's not too much.

1048
00:43:38,682 --> 00:43:39,683
SAVORING

1049
00:43:39,750 --> 00:43:43,821
I think the most accurate expression is
deliciousness meets deliciousness.

1050
00:43:43,887 --> 00:43:45,322
AN UNFAMILIAR MIX
OF DELICIOUS THINGS

1051
00:43:45,389 --> 00:43:47,825
Deliciousness meets deliciousness.

1052
00:43:47,891 --> 00:43:50,728
Does this dish not exist?
Did you come up with it today?

1053
00:43:50,794 --> 00:43:53,197
-It doesn't exist.
-It doesn't exist.

1054
00:43:53,263 --> 00:43:55,399
-You said this was pork, right?
-Yes.

1055
00:43:55,466 --> 00:43:57,034
I always thought

1056
00:43:57,101 --> 00:43:59,770
fried food could only be made
with frying powder or batter.

1057
00:43:59,837 --> 00:44:02,640
But the texture is new

1058
00:44:02,706 --> 00:44:06,710
when it's made without those,
and I like it.

1059
00:44:06,777 --> 00:44:09,480
When you put frying batter on ribs,

1060
00:44:09,546 --> 00:44:11,649
the dredge will peel off
during the braising process.

1061
00:44:11,715 --> 00:44:15,886
That's why I fried those
without using anything.

1062
00:44:15,953 --> 00:44:19,790
When sweetness covers the salty taste,
it'll be something we're used to.

1063
00:44:19,857 --> 00:44:23,027
But this is curry and salty taste
on top of something sweet.

1064
00:44:23,093 --> 00:44:26,096
I also wondered why no one had sold
something like this before.

1065
00:44:26,163 --> 00:44:28,098
It's such a wonderful mix.

1066
00:44:28,165 --> 00:44:30,501
-I love tacos.
-I see.

1067
00:44:30,567 --> 00:44:31,702
Tacos are great.

1068
00:44:31,769 --> 00:44:34,672
Let's try Chef Jong-won's dish.

1069
00:44:34,738 --> 00:44:36,674
-Taco 84.
-Taco 84.

1070
00:44:36,740 --> 00:44:39,810
It doesn't look spicy.

1071
00:44:39,877 --> 00:44:43,414
-It was probably sriracha.
-Right. He used sriracha.

1072
00:44:43,480 --> 00:44:44,481
YUM

1073
00:44:44,548 --> 00:44:47,818
I used to eat tacos and burritos a lot

1074
00:44:47,885 --> 00:44:51,188
back when I lived in the States.

1075
00:44:51,255 --> 00:44:52,756
It reminds me a lot of those days.

1076
00:44:52,823 --> 00:44:54,291
I see.

1077
00:44:54,358 --> 00:44:55,526
What about you, Chef Eddy?

1078
00:44:55,592 --> 00:44:57,928
When I had the taco…

1079
00:45:00,597 --> 00:45:01,598
Mexico.

1080
00:45:01,665 --> 00:45:04,201
That's a great response.

1081
00:45:04,268 --> 00:45:08,439
And now, let's find out Bong-sik's choice.

1082
00:45:08,505 --> 00:45:10,607
Press one for Lee Yeon-bok.

1083
00:45:11,175 --> 00:45:13,243
Press two for Son Jong-won.

1084
00:45:14,044 --> 00:45:16,313
Please press the button!

1085
00:45:17,147 --> 00:45:18,949
-Okay. I did.
-Okay.

1086
00:45:19,016 --> 00:45:21,952
Should I try to guess what his choice was?

1087
00:45:22,019 --> 00:45:24,822
You had an idea of who Bong-sik chose?

1088
00:45:24,888 --> 00:45:27,658
-Yes.
-Last week, they went different ways.

1089
00:45:27,725 --> 00:45:29,860
I liked Su-Su-Su-Super Udon.

1090
00:45:30,494 --> 00:45:33,430
SON SUK-KU CHOSE PARK EUN-YEONG

1091
00:45:33,497 --> 00:45:34,998
I'd pick Chef Edward.

1092
00:45:35,065 --> 00:45:37,801
Son Suk-ku is here to choose. Who won?

1093
00:45:38,368 --> 00:45:41,371
AGAIN, SUK-KU CHOSE THE OTHER CHEF
IN THE NEXT ROUND!

1094
00:45:41,438 --> 00:45:43,340
Which button
did you think Bong-sik pressed?

1095
00:45:44,308 --> 00:45:46,910
Dip It in Curry.

1096
00:45:46,977 --> 00:45:48,879
-Dip It in Curry.
-Dip It in Curry.

1097
00:45:48,946 --> 00:45:50,814
Dip It in Curry. Really?

1098
00:45:50,881 --> 00:45:52,649
-I think that was his choice.
-Really?

1099
00:45:52,716 --> 00:45:54,952
-I think that was his choice.
-Really?

1100
00:45:55,018 --> 00:45:57,788
-He's putting on an act.
-He's acting.

1101
00:45:57,855 --> 00:45:59,957
-I have no idea.
-I really can't tell.

1102
00:46:00,023 --> 00:46:02,593
This is why he's an actor.

1103
00:46:02,659 --> 00:46:03,994
He's such an actor.

1104
00:46:04,061 --> 00:46:06,697
WILL SUK-KU'S PREDICTION
COME TO PASS?

1105
00:46:06,764 --> 00:46:09,967
Is Suk-ku's prediction correct?

1106
00:46:10,033 --> 00:46:13,070
Let's find out which one Bong-sik chose!

1107
00:46:13,137 --> 00:46:15,172
Which chef won?

1108
00:46:15,239 --> 00:46:17,708
These were for his order,
"A dish with Hyun Bong Sixth Sense twist."

1109
00:46:17,775 --> 00:46:19,643
Will it be Lee Yeon-bok,
the long-standing powerhouse?

1110
00:46:19,710 --> 00:46:22,946
Or will it be
the new powerhouse, Son Jong-won?

1111
00:46:23,013 --> 00:46:26,283
Who did Bong-sik choose?

1112
00:46:26,984 --> 00:46:28,752
Let's see the result.

1113
00:46:28,819 --> 00:46:30,154
Who gave a bigger twist?

1114
00:46:30,888 --> 00:46:32,189
Show us!

1115
00:46:33,557 --> 00:46:34,758
Show us!

1116
00:46:34,825 --> 00:46:35,959
LEE YEON-BOK WINS

1117
00:46:36,026 --> 00:46:37,628
CHEF LEE YEON-BOK'S
DIP IT IN CURRY WINS

1118
00:46:37,694 --> 00:46:41,565
Lee Yeon-bok! Chef Yeon-bok was chosen.

1119
00:46:42,065 --> 00:46:44,701
Suk-ku's prediction was correct.

1120
00:46:44,768 --> 00:46:46,236
THAT'S A BUMMER

1121
00:46:46,737 --> 00:46:48,472
WHY DID YOU PICK HIM?

1122
00:46:48,539 --> 00:46:50,407
These were dishes I knew

1123
00:46:50,474 --> 00:46:53,143
made with ingredients I always get.

1124
00:46:53,210 --> 00:46:55,512
-It's like Suk-ku.
-Yes.

1125
00:46:55,579 --> 00:46:57,714
I know Suk-ku very well,

1126
00:46:57,781 --> 00:46:59,616
but he's someone else in his work.

1127
00:47:00,851 --> 00:47:04,521
The man I know isn't on the screen.

1128
00:47:04,588 --> 00:47:06,223
-Right.
-He looks different.

1129
00:47:06,290 --> 00:47:08,358
It was especially so for the pork ribs.

1130
00:47:08,425 --> 00:47:11,962
No matter how hard I tried,
despite my lack of knowledge,

1131
00:47:12,029 --> 00:47:13,664
it always turned out too dry.

1132
00:47:14,264 --> 00:47:15,265
I see.

1133
00:47:15,332 --> 00:47:18,669
Although he only had
a small amount of time to cook,

1134
00:47:18,735 --> 00:47:21,038
it was still juicy on the inside.

1135
00:47:21,104 --> 00:47:23,340
-You must know Bong-sik well.
-Of course.

1136
00:47:23,407 --> 00:47:25,108
-I see.
-I can guess correctly next time too.

1137
00:47:25,175 --> 00:47:27,444
WE LOOK FORWARD TO THAT

1138
00:47:27,511 --> 00:47:30,480
I felt a bit anxious
when Suk-ku said it was me

1139
00:47:30,547 --> 00:47:33,150
before the final result was revealed,

1140
00:47:33,217 --> 00:47:35,118
thinking it could be the other way again.

1141
00:47:35,185 --> 00:47:39,223
I'm very glad that my dish was
appetizing to your taste, Bong-sik.

1142
00:47:39,857 --> 00:47:40,858
CONGRATULATIONS

1143
00:47:40,924 --> 00:47:43,660
Chef Yeon-bok now has three wins.

1144
00:47:43,727 --> 00:47:45,429
He gets his third star!

1145
00:47:45,495 --> 00:47:47,497
You're now in joint first place.

1146
00:47:47,564 --> 00:47:49,566
-Congratulations, Chef Yeon-bok.
-Congratulations.

1147
00:47:50,300 --> 00:47:55,105
CHEF LEE YEON-BOK'S DIP IT IN CURRY
THE RECIPE

1148
00:47:55,172 --> 00:48:00,143
<i>And now, the second round</i>
<i>with ingredients from Bong-sik's fridge.</i>

1149
00:48:00,210 --> 00:48:03,180
It's a fight between two men
who fought three times and have never won,

1150
00:48:03,247 --> 00:48:05,782
the two no-star contestants.

1151
00:48:05,849 --> 00:48:08,185
Great news is that one of you will

1152
00:48:08,252 --> 00:48:11,521
-definitely end up with a star today.
-That's true.

1153
00:48:11,588 --> 00:48:13,457
-They can't run anymore.
-It's a big match.

1154
00:48:13,523 --> 00:48:14,791
And this man

1155
00:48:14,858 --> 00:48:18,695
came today with a different cap.

1156
00:48:18,762 --> 00:48:23,100
He came with the attitude
to turn over into the darker side.

1157
00:48:23,166 --> 00:48:26,136
Chef Kang-rok,
how determined are you today?

1158
00:48:26,203 --> 00:48:30,707
-Yes, so, it wasn't easy to be this dark.
-Right.

1159
00:48:30,774 --> 00:48:31,975
And I like my opponent.

1160
00:48:32,042 --> 00:48:35,479
HE'S UP AGAINST NO-STAR KIM POONG

1161
00:48:35,545 --> 00:48:38,148
I've already become dark,

1162
00:48:38,215 --> 00:48:39,483
so I'm not scared of losing.

1163
00:48:40,751 --> 00:48:42,119
I can even lose 30 times.

1164
00:48:42,185 --> 00:48:43,854
-Thirty?
-Because of your change?

1165
00:48:43,921 --> 00:48:45,689
-That's something scary.
-Yes.

1166
00:48:45,756 --> 00:48:47,858
He came ready to fight today.

1167
00:48:47,925 --> 00:48:50,227
If you lose again today,

1168
00:48:50,294 --> 00:48:52,296
why don't you take your cap off entirely?

1169
00:48:52,362 --> 00:48:53,864
-Like a pledge?
-Yes.

1170
00:48:53,931 --> 00:48:55,299
I'm sure he'll win.

1171
00:48:55,365 --> 00:48:57,200
That's not a big deal.

1172
00:48:57,267 --> 00:48:58,936
I can take it off even now.

1173
00:48:59,503 --> 00:49:01,605
WE THOUGHT THAT CAP
WAS IMPORTANT TO YOU

1174
00:49:01,672 --> 00:49:04,508
People think he's going bald.

1175
00:49:05,609 --> 00:49:09,246
-That he's losing hair?
-There can be such misunderstandings.

1176
00:49:09,313 --> 00:49:11,248
If you lose today,

1177
00:49:11,315 --> 00:49:13,650
-come without a cap for the next shoot.
-Take it off.

1178
00:49:13,717 --> 00:49:15,385
LOOKING OVER

1179
00:49:15,452 --> 00:49:16,887
-Okay.
-Yes.

1180
00:49:16,954 --> 00:49:18,455
I'll take off his cap.

1181
00:49:20,023 --> 00:49:23,327
Artist Poong, did you bring
the frying pan from Chef Sung-jun?

1182
00:49:23,393 --> 00:49:27,064
-Yes, I'll use my Sylvia today.
-Sylvia?

1183
00:49:27,130 --> 00:49:28,832
I'm here with Sylvia.

1184
00:49:28,899 --> 00:49:29,900
-Sylvia.
-Yes.

1185
00:49:29,967 --> 00:49:31,101
He named it.

1186
00:49:31,168 --> 00:49:32,536
-You named it?
-Yes.

1187
00:49:32,602 --> 00:49:33,770
-Sylvia?
-Yes.

1188
00:49:33,837 --> 00:49:37,207
The thing is,
as soon as I gave that pan away to him,

1189
00:49:37,274 --> 00:49:38,275
I won.

1190
00:49:39,242 --> 00:49:41,078
-What?
-That's true.

1191
00:49:41,144 --> 00:49:42,279
It's a curse, not Sylvia.

1192
00:49:42,346 --> 00:49:44,514
-It must be out of its luck.
-Wait.

1193
00:49:44,581 --> 00:49:46,917
-That's true.
-Come to think of it, yes.

1194
00:49:46,984 --> 00:49:50,587
-It must be out of luck.
-I have a bad feeling about this.

1195
00:49:50,654 --> 00:49:53,290
One came with a cap,
and the other came with a frying pan.

1196
00:49:53,357 --> 00:49:55,392
-Something is adding up.
-Yes.

1197
00:49:55,459 --> 00:50:00,630
The previous two chefs
did not use any perks,

1198
00:50:00,697 --> 00:50:02,966
so you're free to use one each.

1199
00:50:03,033 --> 00:50:05,569
First of all, on this side,

1200
00:50:06,269 --> 00:50:08,238
-his colleagues are getting ready.
-They're ready.

1201
00:50:08,305 --> 00:50:10,674
-They have something.
-Yes.

1202
00:50:10,741 --> 00:50:14,244
-I can tell what he'll use.
-He put it out there.

1203
00:50:14,311 --> 00:50:17,581
Think of how worried I was
to put three of them to use.

1204
00:50:17,647 --> 00:50:20,317
So your entire team will
become your UNICHEF?

1205
00:50:20,384 --> 00:50:23,754
Yes, I had
lots of ingredients to chop today.

1206
00:50:23,820 --> 00:50:28,058
I'd like to use the UNICHEF perk
and ask them to help me chop.

1207
00:50:28,125 --> 00:50:29,359
For the ingredient.

1208
00:50:29,426 --> 00:50:31,028
I have to use them as soon as I begin.

1209
00:50:31,094 --> 00:50:33,997
I'll also use the UNICHEF perk.

1210
00:50:34,064 --> 00:50:35,399
How many do you need?

1211
00:50:35,465 --> 00:50:38,502
-I just need one person.
-One person.

1212
00:50:38,568 --> 00:50:40,137
But you will not use it
as soon as you begin?

1213
00:50:40,203 --> 00:50:42,439
No, not as soon as I begin.

1214
00:50:42,506 --> 00:50:45,175
-I'll need him toward the end.
-Toward the end.

1215
00:50:45,242 --> 00:50:47,210
Are you going to ask Bong-sik
toward the end?

1216
00:50:47,978 --> 00:50:48,979
May I do that?

1217
00:50:49,046 --> 00:50:50,147
IS HE USING UNI-BONG-SIK?

1218
00:50:50,213 --> 00:50:53,116
-He may ask him to taste his food.
-Yes. "Does this taste okay?"

1219
00:50:53,183 --> 00:50:55,419
It'd be the best
if I could ask him to taste it.

1220
00:50:56,253 --> 00:50:58,321
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
ANCHOVY SAUCE, WHOLE WHEAT SPAGHETTI

1221
00:50:58,388 --> 00:51:00,424
SHRIMP, CHICKEN POWDER, SLICED BEEF LOIN,
CABBAGE, PERILLA LEAVES

1222
00:51:00,490 --> 00:51:02,893
The dish I'm making is called

1223
00:51:02,959 --> 00:51:04,895
Napoli Poongfia.

1224
00:51:04,961 --> 00:51:06,963
-"Napoli Poongfia"?
-"Napoli Poongfia"?

1225
00:51:07,030 --> 00:51:09,366
-Not Napoli Matfia?
-No.

1226
00:51:09,433 --> 00:51:11,868
Are you saying
you're going to follow his path?

1227
00:51:11,935 --> 00:51:13,370
What's the dish?

1228
00:51:13,437 --> 00:51:17,607
-Sylvia had wanted to make pasta.
-Right.

1229
00:51:17,674 --> 00:51:21,478
I thought I should make pasta too.

1230
00:51:21,545 --> 00:51:22,913
I'm going to make pasta

1231
00:51:22,979 --> 00:51:25,782
with a touch of Kim Poong

1232
00:51:25,849 --> 00:51:28,718
-by mixing in a hint of Chinese.
-A hint of Chinese?

1233
00:51:28,785 --> 00:51:32,122
So I'll make Chinese-style pasta.

1234
00:51:32,189 --> 00:51:34,524
-Chinese-style pasta?
-Chinese-style pasta?

1235
00:51:34,591 --> 00:51:36,059
That sounds good.

1236
00:51:36,126 --> 00:51:38,995
The order is Noodle Bong-sik.

1237
00:51:39,062 --> 00:51:42,466
He said he'd make pasta
with a hint of Chinese.

1238
00:51:43,300 --> 00:51:47,904
CHEF CHOI KANG-ROK'S INGREDIENTS:

1239
00:51:47,971 --> 00:51:52,476
CHICKEN POWDER, BUCKWHEAT NOODLES,
DRIED LAVER FLAKES, SHRIMP

1240
00:51:52,542 --> 00:51:55,479
Chef Kang-rok, what's your noodle dish?

1241
00:51:55,545 --> 00:51:57,314
I'm going to make

1242
00:51:57,380 --> 00:52:01,118
D.P. Buckwheat Noodles.

1243
00:52:01,184 --> 00:52:03,253
-D.P. Buckwheat Noodles.
-D.P. Buckwheat Noodles.

1244
00:52:03,320 --> 00:52:04,955
-D.P. Buckwheat Noodles.
-Yes.

1245
00:52:05,021 --> 00:52:07,724
D.P. as in the military?

1246
00:52:08,425 --> 00:52:09,593
It stands for <i>daepa</i>, green onion.

1247
00:52:09,659 --> 00:52:12,429
-I see. D.P., <i>daepa</i>.
-I see.

1248
00:52:12,496 --> 00:52:14,297
I see. Green onion and buckwheat noodles.

1249
00:52:14,364 --> 00:52:19,402
Vegetables can give off
very delicious flavor.

1250
00:52:19,469 --> 00:52:23,373
-Yes.
-I'll use as much green onion as I can

1251
00:52:23,440 --> 00:52:26,343
and bring out as much flavor as possible

1252
00:52:26,409 --> 00:52:30,514
to make a noodle dish
he can eat easily just as he wants.

1253
00:52:30,580 --> 00:52:34,518
I'll make a noodle dish

1254
00:52:34,584 --> 00:52:36,887
he'll slurp down easily.

1255
00:52:36,953 --> 00:52:38,455
I see. Okay.

1256
00:52:38,522 --> 00:52:40,390
He's making pasta,
he's making buckwheat noodles.

1257
00:52:40,457 --> 00:52:43,193
Yes, he's making buckwheat noodles.
That sounds good.

1258
00:52:43,260 --> 00:52:45,495
Let us begin the round "Noodle Bong-sik."

1259
00:52:46,229 --> 00:52:49,933
He gives off a dark aura
from his dark cap.

1260
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:53,436
Chef Kang-rok is up,
after becoming Mr. Darkness.

1261
00:52:53,970 --> 00:52:55,505
"Mr. Darkness"?

1262
00:52:55,572 --> 00:52:57,240
LAUGHING QUIETLY

1263
00:52:59,176 --> 00:53:01,845
He's up against this man
who'll use the frying pan

1264
00:53:01,912 --> 00:53:05,282
from the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>
to make Chef Kang-rok's future more grim,

1265
00:53:05,348 --> 00:53:08,652
Cook of the Darkness, Kim Poong.

1266
00:53:08,718 --> 00:53:12,556
They face this deadly match at the edge
of their demise after three losses.

1267
00:53:12,622 --> 00:53:15,892
Let us begin the 15-minute cook-off!

1268
00:53:17,127 --> 00:53:18,361
Let us begin!

1269
00:53:18,428 --> 00:53:20,397
CHEF KANG-ROK USES 1-MINUTE UNICHEF
AS SOON AS HE BEGINS

1270
00:53:20,463 --> 00:53:22,766
-Very thinly, just the white portion.
-Very thinly.

1271
00:53:22,832 --> 00:53:25,902
-Make them very thin.
-He must be using lots of green onions.

1272
00:53:27,304 --> 00:53:28,638
CHICKEN POWDER

1273
00:53:29,139 --> 00:53:32,409
1. BOIL WATER WITH CHICKEN POWDER
AND MAKE BROTH

1274
00:53:33,076 --> 00:53:38,114
Three people are chopping green onion
all at the same time.

1275
00:53:38,181 --> 00:53:39,816
ALL OF UNICHEF
ARE CHOPPING GREEN ONION

1276
00:53:39,883 --> 00:53:41,518
Do you need this much green onion?

1277
00:53:41,585 --> 00:53:42,919
What's with all the noise?

1278
00:53:43,620 --> 00:53:44,621
BE QUIET!

1279
00:53:44,688 --> 00:53:45,689
Three of them are at it.

1280
00:53:45,755 --> 00:53:46,756
GARLIC CLOVE

1281
00:53:46,823 --> 00:53:47,824
GREEN ONION

1282
00:53:48,725 --> 00:53:50,627
THEY GO INTO SIMMERING OIL

1283
00:53:51,962 --> 00:53:55,432
1. BOIL GARLIC, GREEN ONION,
AND RED PEPPER POWDER TO MAKE CHILI OIL

1284
00:53:55,498 --> 00:53:57,434
It's as if we'll begin a party.

1285
00:53:58,468 --> 00:54:00,003
-All three of them.
-It feels like the holidays.

1286
00:54:00,070 --> 00:54:02,772
-Yes, it's that vibe.
-Yes.

1287
00:54:03,673 --> 00:54:04,874
CHILI PEPPER, GREEN ONION

1288
00:54:04,941 --> 00:54:08,111
-They have such good teamwork.
-Yes.

1289
00:54:08,178 --> 00:54:10,714
We can only offer you 1 minute,
and you have 40 seconds left.

1290
00:54:11,615 --> 00:54:14,451
Chef Kang-rok uses
the UNICHEF perk right away.

1291
00:54:15,318 --> 00:54:17,254
He only washed kimchi for me.

1292
00:54:17,754 --> 00:54:19,623
CHEF EUN-YEONG TOOK A BLOW
FROM MR. SLOW AS HER UNICHEF

1293
00:54:19,689 --> 00:54:21,491
The three don't have enough time.

1294
00:54:21,558 --> 00:54:22,659
That's a lot.

1295
00:54:22,726 --> 00:54:23,727
You have 30 seconds.

1296
00:54:24,394 --> 00:54:26,263
Thirty seconds.
You can't help out for too long.

1297
00:54:27,230 --> 00:54:29,032
You only get a minute.

1298
00:54:29,899 --> 00:54:31,234
Is there more green onion?

1299
00:54:32,068 --> 00:54:33,470
-There is.
-There is, Chef Edward.

1300
00:54:33,536 --> 00:54:36,072
You have ten seconds left.

1301
00:54:36,740 --> 00:54:39,743
Green onion. <i>Daepa</i>. D.P.

1302
00:54:40,610 --> 00:54:42,612
Five. Four.

1303
00:54:42,679 --> 00:54:45,348
Three. Two. One.

1304
00:54:45,415 --> 00:54:46,950
-That's all.
-You're done.

1305
00:54:47,017 --> 00:54:50,153
You can take the ones they cut until now.

1306
00:54:50,220 --> 00:54:51,221
THANKS

1307
00:54:51,288 --> 00:54:53,423
He used up his minute.

1308
00:54:54,257 --> 00:54:56,893
These three have too much experience
to just cut up green onions.

1309
00:54:56,960 --> 00:55:00,797
-Yes, it probably has been a while.
-Yes.

1310
00:55:00,864 --> 00:55:02,632
He must be using lots of green onions.

1311
00:55:02,699 --> 00:55:04,167
Yes, he must be.

1312
00:55:04,234 --> 00:55:07,170
KIM POONG ALSO CUTS GREEN ONION

1313
00:55:07,737 --> 00:55:10,607
2. CUT GREEN ONION INTO THIN SLICES

1314
00:55:11,107 --> 00:55:12,442
-Artist Poong!
-Yes?

1315
00:55:12,509 --> 00:55:14,778
Borrow some green onion
from your neighbor. It's taking too long.

1316
00:55:14,844 --> 00:55:16,846
-He used it up.
-He did?

1317
00:55:16,913 --> 00:55:18,481
Gosh, I could've stolen some.

1318
00:55:18,548 --> 00:55:20,383
-They chopped like half a dozen.
-Is he making soup?

1319
00:55:20,450 --> 00:55:24,654
The green onion will make the broth
just like meat.

1320
00:55:24,721 --> 00:55:26,656
-Were those for the broth?
-But it's not meat.

1321
00:55:26,723 --> 00:55:28,458
-You won't use the green onion?
-What?

1322
00:55:28,525 --> 00:55:29,693
You'll only use the veggie broth?

1323
00:55:29,759 --> 00:55:30,960
Well, it's…

1324
00:55:31,027 --> 00:55:32,462
It's like… Yes.

1325
00:55:34,631 --> 00:55:36,933
-Go back to cooking.
-Start cooking.

1326
00:55:37,000 --> 00:55:38,535
-No.
-We shouldn't talk to him.

1327
00:55:39,102 --> 00:55:41,271
Can you really make broth
with green onion?

1328
00:55:41,338 --> 00:55:42,539
Why are you looking at that?

1329
00:55:42,605 --> 00:55:45,442
-Are you making broth?
-Hurry up!

1330
00:55:45,508 --> 00:55:48,044
He started talking to him
after we stopped.

1331
00:55:48,111 --> 00:55:50,280
Artist Poong just made chili oil.

1332
00:55:50,347 --> 00:55:52,716
-Chili oil.
-Yes.

1333
00:55:52,782 --> 00:55:56,586
He always makes chili oil first.

1334
00:55:57,487 --> 00:55:59,255
-That's the key.
-I see.

1335
00:55:59,322 --> 00:56:00,990
Sylvia gets heated.

1336
00:56:01,057 --> 00:56:03,860
-Sylvia finally shows up.
-Sylvia!

1337
00:56:03,927 --> 00:56:05,195
A gift from Chef Sung-jun.

1338
00:56:05,261 --> 00:56:06,963
But I haven't used this.

1339
00:56:07,530 --> 00:56:09,532
-My goodness.
-What now?

1340
00:56:09,599 --> 00:56:10,867
-He only carried it around.
-Yes.

1341
00:56:10,934 --> 00:56:12,435
Some say you carry it on your back.

1342
00:56:12,502 --> 00:56:14,637
MY PRECIOUS TREASURE, SYLVIA

1343
00:56:15,472 --> 00:56:16,906
SWIFT

1344
00:56:17,507 --> 00:56:19,609
FLOUR?

1345
00:56:19,676 --> 00:56:22,479
-Chef Kang-rok makes batter.
-What's it for?

1346
00:56:22,545 --> 00:56:23,947
I think it's to make fritter.

1347
00:56:24,013 --> 00:56:25,115
Is he making batter?

1348
00:56:25,181 --> 00:56:27,717
-Is that for fritter?
-Yes, it is.

1349
00:56:28,485 --> 00:56:29,753
And… Yes.

1350
00:56:30,320 --> 00:56:32,622
Bong-sik said he liked dried laver flakes.

1351
00:56:32,689 --> 00:56:34,524
MOUTH WATERING

1352
00:56:35,024 --> 00:56:38,261
He added lots of dried laver flakes
into the batter.

1353
00:56:38,328 --> 00:56:40,296
He's adding laver flakes to the batter.

1354
00:56:40,363 --> 00:56:42,899
-Is he making laver fritters?
-That's a lot.

1355
00:56:42,966 --> 00:56:46,136
Chef Kang-rok, why did you add
dried laver flakes into the batter?

1356
00:56:46,903 --> 00:56:48,238
It's better than not putting it in.

1357
00:56:49,506 --> 00:56:51,341
It's better than not putting it in.

1358
00:56:53,476 --> 00:56:55,612
THAT WAS AN UNEXPECTED REASON

1359
00:56:55,678 --> 00:56:57,514
-That's a great quote.
-That is.

1360
00:56:58,081 --> 00:56:59,616
"It's better than not putting it in."

1361
00:56:59,682 --> 00:57:01,618
That's a valid point.

1362
00:57:01,684 --> 00:57:04,020
AND HE LAYS OUT FRYING POWDER
ON A WIDE PLATE

1363
00:57:04,087 --> 00:57:06,856
-Chef Kang-rok will fry shrimp.
-Shrimp.

1364
00:57:06,923 --> 00:57:08,591
He'll probably fry shrimp.

1365
00:57:08,658 --> 00:57:13,163
It's already been cleaned,
so it's very easy to fry.

1366
00:57:13,229 --> 00:57:15,398
The shrimps are helping out a lot.

1367
00:57:15,465 --> 00:57:17,100
-They come in perfect sizes too.
-Yes.

1368
00:57:17,167 --> 00:57:18,701
And it'll stay in a pretty shape.

1369
00:57:18,768 --> 00:57:20,370
You also won thanks to that.

1370
00:57:20,437 --> 00:57:22,372
-Yes, I did.
-Yes, it helped you cook.

1371
00:57:22,439 --> 00:57:26,309
So he'll dip the shrimp
into the laver batter and fry that?

1372
00:57:26,376 --> 00:57:28,211
-Yes.
-I think so.

1373
00:57:28,278 --> 00:57:30,447
-I think that's it.
-That's amazing.

1374
00:57:32,182 --> 00:57:33,183
Okay.

1375
00:57:33,249 --> 00:57:34,851
CHECKING THE TEMPERATURE
WITH THE BATTER

1376
00:57:34,918 --> 00:57:36,019
Oh.

1377
00:57:36,085 --> 00:57:37,654
-But the laver…
-Oh.

1378
00:57:38,455 --> 00:57:41,191
-It's not hot.
-It's not on.

1379
00:57:41,257 --> 00:57:44,127
-Wait, the oil.
-It wasn't turned on.

1380
00:57:44,194 --> 00:57:46,229
The oil did not heat up.

1381
00:57:46,296 --> 00:57:48,565
HE LEFT THE OIL THERE
WITHOUT TURNING THE HEAT UP

1382
00:57:48,631 --> 00:57:49,699
YOU GOT NEGLECTED

1383
00:57:49,766 --> 00:57:52,969
-This is bad.
-It must be about 70 degrees.

1384
00:57:53,036 --> 00:57:55,738
This is bad.
It's supposed to fry in high heat.

1385
00:57:55,805 --> 00:57:57,373
You should turn the heat up.

1386
00:57:57,440 --> 00:57:59,175
-Turn both stoves on.
-Turn it up.

1387
00:57:59,242 --> 00:58:01,244
-Turn it up higher.
-The middle one isn't on.

1388
00:58:02,312 --> 00:58:06,316
HE EVEN TURNS
THE LIGHT ON DELICATELY

1389
00:58:08,284 --> 00:58:11,454
The color of Poong's chili oil
looks great.

1390
00:58:11,521 --> 00:58:12,755
You can tell by the color?

1391
00:58:12,822 --> 00:58:14,557
-Yes.
-It smells so good.

1392
00:58:14,624 --> 00:58:16,993
He's chopping cabbage.

1393
00:58:17,060 --> 00:58:19,095
Artist Poong chops napa cabbage.

1394
00:58:19,162 --> 00:58:21,564
He said this was Chinese-style pasta.

1395
00:58:21,631 --> 00:58:23,833
-Are you using cabbage for the pasta?
-Yes.

1396
00:58:23,900 --> 00:58:26,102
-And garlic.
-He's adding more garlic.

1397
00:58:26,803 --> 00:58:29,405
And I have 11 minutes.

1398
00:58:29,472 --> 00:58:31,474
-Put it in.
-Do I have to put it in now?

1399
00:58:31,541 --> 00:58:32,575
-You do.
-I do?

1400
00:58:32,642 --> 00:58:35,879
Who are you asking?
You need to do this alone.

1401
00:58:35,945 --> 00:58:38,381
Who were you asking
about putting that in right now?

1402
00:58:38,448 --> 00:58:40,083
MR. POONG BECAME
KWON SUNG-JUN'S AVATAR

1403
00:58:40,149 --> 00:58:41,484
He's Poongfia.

1404
00:58:41,551 --> 00:58:43,086
Stop trying to be cool and throw it in.

1405
00:58:43,152 --> 00:58:44,787
I have to do this
to prevent it from sticking.

1406
00:58:44,854 --> 00:58:46,890
I know, but you're in a hurry right now.

1407
00:58:47,624 --> 00:58:50,026
He's cooking the pasta first.

1408
00:58:50,093 --> 00:58:52,362
Chef Sung-jun, what's that pasta?

1409
00:58:52,428 --> 00:58:54,797
-It's whole wheat pasta.
-Whole wheat?

1410
00:58:54,864 --> 00:58:56,733
-What did you just put in?
-What?

1411
00:58:56,799 --> 00:58:59,636
-Chicken powder. Chicken stock.
-Chicken stock?

1412
00:58:59,702 --> 00:59:02,772
-He's seasoning the pasta.
-I see.

1413
00:59:02,839 --> 00:59:04,707
-The pasta will taste great.
-Yes.

1414
00:59:04,774 --> 00:59:07,277
-He's using a product.
-Yes.

1415
00:59:07,343 --> 00:59:08,978
You have under ten minutes left.

1416
00:59:09,045 --> 00:59:10,246
ALREADY?

1417
00:59:11,648 --> 00:59:15,451
Chef Kang-rok begins to cook
the buckwheat noodles as we speak.

1418
00:59:15,518 --> 00:59:17,554
He's cooking buckwheat noodles.

1419
00:59:17,620 --> 00:59:19,722
And there's the green onion broth.

1420
00:59:19,789 --> 00:59:21,057
AND WAITING

1421
00:59:21,124 --> 00:59:22,292
The shrimp goes in.

1422
00:59:23,259 --> 00:59:25,261
Is it ready?
Is the temperature high enough?

1423
00:59:25,328 --> 00:59:28,031
-I think it is.
-Yes, it's working.

1424
00:59:28,097 --> 00:59:29,599
Yes, Chef Kang-rok.

1425
00:59:30,733 --> 00:59:32,969
I love the sound of deep-frying.

1426
00:59:33,736 --> 00:59:35,605
Will the laver help with the batter?

1427
00:59:35,672 --> 00:59:37,574
-It'll add the laver flavor.
-The flavor.

1428
00:59:37,640 --> 00:59:40,677
That and it'll add a savory taste
because it's seasoned.

1429
00:59:41,244 --> 00:59:44,347
-It may taste like laver chips.
-Like laver chips.

1430
00:59:45,515 --> 00:59:47,517
THE PROBLEM IS THIS MAN

1431
00:59:48,384 --> 00:59:52,789
7. STIR-FRY SLICED BEEF LOIN
IN THE PAN WITH CHILI OIL AND GARLIC

1432
00:59:54,324 --> 00:59:56,559
Why is it so hot?

1433
00:59:56,626 --> 00:59:58,761
STUCK

1434
00:59:58,828 --> 00:59:59,829
It sticks easily.

1435
00:59:59,896 --> 01:00:01,397
Why is it getting stuck?

1436
01:00:01,464 --> 01:00:03,499
It's not coated, so it'll get stuck.

1437
01:00:03,566 --> 01:00:09,038
Artist Poong doesn't really know
how heat is conducted on that pan, Sylvia.

1438
01:00:09,105 --> 01:00:10,206
Something is burning.

1439
01:00:10,273 --> 01:00:12,308
And that Sylvia pan was supposedly cursed.

1440
01:00:14,277 --> 01:00:16,946
-No, Sylvia did nothing wrong.
-Sylvia's curse.

1441
01:00:19,382 --> 01:00:21,384
Why wasn't it coated?

1442
01:00:21,451 --> 01:00:23,119
You have to coat it with oil.

1443
01:00:23,186 --> 01:00:25,421
You have to heat it in high heat
and coat it with oil.

1444
01:00:25,488 --> 01:00:26,489
Really?

1445
01:00:26,556 --> 01:00:27,690
I'll add some cabbage.

1446
01:00:27,757 --> 01:00:28,992
HOW ABOUT SOME CABBAGE?

1447
01:00:29,058 --> 01:00:30,793
Doesn't Sylvia look burnt?

1448
01:00:30,860 --> 01:00:32,729
-Sylvia's burnt.
-No, it's not.

1449
01:00:32,795 --> 01:00:34,130
But it's scorched and stuck.

1450
01:00:34,197 --> 01:00:36,299
-But it shouldn't get stuck.
-Sylvia.

1451
01:00:36,366 --> 01:00:37,567
The heat conduction…

1452
01:00:37,634 --> 01:00:39,002
You can add some pasta water.

1453
01:00:39,068 --> 01:00:40,970
-I can add some pasta water?
-Yes.

1454
01:00:41,037 --> 01:00:43,906
He's getting mentored by him.

1455
01:00:43,973 --> 01:00:46,042
And he listens to everything.

1456
01:00:46,109 --> 01:00:47,543
Yes, you should add pasta water.

1457
01:00:47,610 --> 01:00:49,345
That way, the cabbage won't get stuck.

1458
01:00:49,412 --> 01:00:51,147
I see. Yes.

1459
01:00:51,214 --> 01:00:53,716
Chef Kang-rok, you're…

1460
01:00:53,783 --> 01:00:56,352
-Whoa.
-He's on fire!

1461
01:00:56,419 --> 01:00:58,021
Chef Kang-rok, you're…

1462
01:00:58,921 --> 01:01:03,559
THOSE WHO DO NOT QUALIFY
ARE NOT ALLOWED TO HANDLE SYLVIA

1463
01:01:03,626 --> 01:01:05,061
He's on fire!

1464
01:01:05,128 --> 01:01:08,064
-What's wrong with this?
-What now?

1465
01:01:08,131 --> 01:01:10,433
-Stay calm.
-Poong, is it all burnt?

1466
01:01:11,100 --> 01:01:12,135
It's a good thing.

1467
01:01:12,201 --> 01:01:13,870
It's good to set it on a light fire.

1468
01:01:13,936 --> 01:01:15,805
-It'll add a smoky taste.
-Is that okay?

1469
01:01:15,872 --> 01:01:18,775
The problem is that
he's surprised at his own doing.

1470
01:01:18,841 --> 01:01:22,912
He wasn't trying to set it on fire.
It just happened.

1471
01:01:22,979 --> 01:01:25,682
Should we think of this as luck?

1472
01:01:25,748 --> 01:01:27,817
-How will that end up affecting him?
-Right.

1473
01:01:27,884 --> 01:01:30,520
ADD NAPA CABBAGE, PASTA WATER,
AND ANCHOVY SAUCE TO MAKE PASTA SAUCE

1474
01:01:31,821 --> 01:01:32,822
Huh?

1475
01:01:34,524 --> 01:01:36,459
SPECIAL BROTH
WITH HALF GREEN ONION AND HALF WATER

1476
01:01:36,526 --> 01:01:37,527
What?

1477
01:01:37,593 --> 01:01:39,562
Oh. Whoa.

1478
01:01:39,629 --> 01:01:41,230
-Goodness.
-What is it?

1479
01:01:41,297 --> 01:01:42,298
What's wrong?

1480
01:01:43,466 --> 01:01:45,101
Don't throw it out!

1481
01:01:45,168 --> 01:01:46,202
Don't throw it out!

1482
01:01:46,269 --> 01:01:48,271
THE BROTH IS SAFELY IN THE BOWL

1483
01:01:48,337 --> 01:01:51,307
He almost threw out the green onion broth!

1484
01:01:51,374 --> 01:01:53,376
He almost threw out the broth.

1485
01:01:53,443 --> 01:01:54,477
Really?

1486
01:01:55,211 --> 01:01:57,914
-He almost threw out the broth.
-Yes.

1487
01:01:57,980 --> 01:01:59,549
That was such a dangerous moment.

1488
01:01:59,615 --> 01:02:03,252
He was trying to use that broth
to make his dish.

1489
01:02:03,319 --> 01:02:05,488
-He almost threw it out.
-I can't believe it.

1490
01:02:06,456 --> 01:02:08,458
Choi Kang-rok looks nervous again.

1491
01:02:09,158 --> 01:02:11,160
My goodness.

1492
01:02:11,227 --> 01:02:13,830
-He almost threw it out like that?
-Yes.

1493
01:02:14,397 --> 01:02:16,899
8. DRAIN COOKED BUCKWHEAT NOODLES
AND RINSE WITH COLD WATER

1494
01:02:17,533 --> 01:02:18,668
Goodness.

1495
01:02:18,735 --> 01:02:21,537
Is he still boiling the green onion broth?

1496
01:02:21,604 --> 01:02:23,906
Yes, he'll probably make soup

1497
01:02:23,973 --> 01:02:26,275
with cooking wine and soy sauce.

1498
01:02:26,342 --> 01:02:28,478
-For the buckwheat noodles?
-Yes.

1499
01:02:28,544 --> 01:02:31,881
-Chef Ho-young helps his underclassman.
-Yes.

1500
01:02:31,948 --> 01:02:34,584
-Soy sauce. He's making the sauce.
-Soy sauce.

1501
01:02:34,650 --> 01:02:36,352
SMELLS TO CHECK IF IT'S SOY SAUCE

1502
01:02:36,419 --> 01:02:38,287
And he put it in the green onion broth.

1503
01:02:38,354 --> 01:02:41,124
9. ADD COOKING WINE, SOY SAUCE, AND BUTTER
TO THE GREEN ONION BROTH AND MAKE SOUP

1504
01:02:41,190 --> 01:02:43,893
He put butter into the green onion broth.

1505
01:02:43,960 --> 01:02:45,128
Will it melt?

1506
01:02:45,194 --> 01:02:47,797
It'll emulsify if he boils it hard enough.

1507
01:02:47,864 --> 01:02:50,233
He's using the green onion too!

1508
01:02:50,299 --> 01:02:51,734
SOME OF THE GREEN ONION
GOES BACK IN

1509
01:02:52,401 --> 01:02:53,402
ATTENTION!

1510
01:02:54,403 --> 01:02:55,538
THE SHRIMP COMES OUT

1511
01:02:55,605 --> 01:02:59,075
A minute or so. It's been a minute…

1512
01:02:59,142 --> 01:03:00,810
-The laver.
-That looks good.

1513
01:03:00,877 --> 01:03:02,779
The dried laver comes out like that.

1514
01:03:03,379 --> 01:03:05,715
-I like the color.
-It's in great shape too.

1515
01:03:05,782 --> 01:03:07,416
That looks good.

1516
01:03:09,252 --> 01:03:10,286
CHECKING THE TIME

1517
01:03:10,353 --> 01:03:12,388
KIM POONG LOOKS SOMEWHAT ANXIOUS

1518
01:03:12,455 --> 01:03:14,290
This pasta is quite thick.

1519
01:03:14,357 --> 01:03:16,993
Do you need a while to cook that pasta?

1520
01:03:17,059 --> 01:03:19,762
-It takes about eight minutes.
-Eight minutes.

1521
01:03:19,829 --> 01:03:22,999
-I cook those for ten minutes.
-You take ten minutes.

1522
01:03:23,065 --> 01:03:25,902
Bong-sik usually cooks that
for ten minutes.

1523
01:03:25,968 --> 01:03:27,670
-He's pulling them out.
-Yes.

1524
01:03:27,737 --> 01:03:30,773
He can just cook it on the pan
with the cabbage.

1525
01:03:30,840 --> 01:03:33,810
-It'll get cooked while it's tossed.
-Yes.

1526
01:03:33,876 --> 01:03:36,712
You need to add the water.
I don't think it'll get cooked.

1527
01:03:36,779 --> 01:03:39,081
-The water?
-Yes, add some to speed it up.

1528
01:03:39,148 --> 01:03:41,150
The pasta is way undercooked.

1529
01:03:41,217 --> 01:03:42,952
-It's still…
-You need much more water.

1530
01:03:43,019 --> 01:03:45,221
-Much more?
-That's not going to get cooked.

1531
01:03:46,055 --> 01:03:47,590
You have to put it on high heat.

1532
01:03:48,157 --> 01:03:51,027
9. ADD PASTA AND PASTA WATER
INTO THE SAUCE AND TOSS

1533
01:03:51,093 --> 01:03:54,363
Artist Poong, the pasta looks too raw.

1534
01:03:54,430 --> 01:03:55,898
-Wait.
-You still have some time.

1535
01:03:55,965 --> 01:03:58,701
-You lost a piece of cabbage.
-It just flew out.

1536
01:03:58,768 --> 01:04:00,770
You have under five minutes now.

1537
01:04:00,837 --> 01:04:03,539
-Jung-hwan, please go out to the field.
-Yes.

1538
01:04:03,606 --> 01:04:05,741
My gosh. Chef Kang-rok.

1539
01:04:05,808 --> 01:04:08,144
-They both have no stars.
-It's not cooked at all.

1540
01:04:08,211 --> 01:04:10,880
Gosh, this is trouble.
Why won't the pasta get cooked?

1541
01:04:10,947 --> 01:04:12,248
He says he's in trouble.

1542
01:04:12,315 --> 01:04:15,184
The pasta is still rigid.

1543
01:04:15,251 --> 01:04:16,819
It's like wire.

1544
01:04:16,886 --> 01:04:18,788
-Wire?
-You can use it…

1545
01:04:18,855 --> 01:04:20,590
to build buildings at this rate.

1546
01:04:20,656 --> 01:04:21,858
-Jung-hwan.
-Yes?

1547
01:04:21,924 --> 01:04:24,760
Why don't you pick up a piece of pasta
and see if it's as hard as wire?

1548
01:04:24,827 --> 01:04:26,295
-Me?
-Right now.

1549
01:04:26,362 --> 01:04:27,363
Gosh, okay.

1550
01:04:27,430 --> 01:04:29,999
Let's find out
how well it's cooked so far.

1551
01:04:32,435 --> 01:04:33,436
Darn it.

1552
01:04:33,502 --> 01:04:35,338
-Be careful.
-What's happening now?

1553
01:04:35,404 --> 01:04:38,808
He's still not used to the pan.
The sauce is flying everywhere.

1554
01:04:38,875 --> 01:04:42,144
Sylvia ended up
in the hands of the wrong owner.

1555
01:04:42,211 --> 01:04:43,913
This pasta is…

1556
01:04:43,980 --> 01:04:45,882
-I'll try the pasta.
-Okay.

1557
01:04:45,948 --> 01:04:49,151
-You can use it for sewing.
-I see.

1558
01:04:49,218 --> 01:04:53,055
It doesn't look cooked, but how far is he?

1559
01:04:53,122 --> 01:04:54,123
What's wrong?

1560
01:04:54,190 --> 01:04:56,125
-Did you spit it out?
-He spit it out.

1561
01:04:56,192 --> 01:04:58,828
-I can't eat this.
-You can't?

1562
01:04:58,895 --> 01:05:01,063
The insides are just…

1563
01:05:01,130 --> 01:05:02,398
Only the outside is slightly cooked.

1564
01:05:02,465 --> 01:05:04,800
It's way undercooked.
The pasta needs to be cooked.

1565
01:05:04,867 --> 01:05:08,671
The fridge owner said
he cooked that pasta for ten minutes.

1566
01:05:08,738 --> 01:05:11,140
It's almost raw.
I like to eat raw ramyeon,

1567
01:05:11,207 --> 01:05:12,241
and it tasted like that.

1568
01:05:12,308 --> 01:05:14,110
Gosh, his dish was ruined.

1569
01:05:14,176 --> 01:05:16,245
-Turn up the heat.
-It needs to be cooked more.

1570
01:05:16,312 --> 01:05:17,947
But the heat won't…

1571
01:05:18,014 --> 01:05:19,548
You don't have much time.

1572
01:05:19,615 --> 01:05:23,286
Chef Kang-rok made nice fried shrimps.

1573
01:05:23,352 --> 01:05:25,454
-He's making it thick.
-Are you adding starch water?

1574
01:05:25,521 --> 01:05:27,556
-Yes.
-He's making it thick.

1575
01:05:27,623 --> 01:05:29,458
So this is the soup
for the noodles, right?

1576
01:05:29,525 --> 01:05:30,993
Yes, it's the soup for the noodles.

1577
01:05:31,827 --> 01:05:32,828
TAPPING

1578
01:05:34,830 --> 01:05:37,700
THE EGG FOR THE SOUP
IS READY TO GO TOO

1579
01:05:38,401 --> 01:05:40,569
AND LASTLY, THE LONG-AWAITED
BUCKWHEAT NOODLES

1580
01:05:41,337 --> 01:05:46,042
11. ADD THE BUCKWHEAT NOODLES
TO THE SOUP AND BRING TO A BOIL

1581
01:05:46,108 --> 01:05:47,576
Hey, wait.

1582
01:05:47,643 --> 01:05:49,712
Is the problem the pan or the pasta?

1583
01:05:50,880 --> 01:05:53,516
The noodles are still raw, right?
It's not cooked.

1584
01:05:53,582 --> 01:05:54,850
-He has a while to go.
-He does, right?

1585
01:05:56,085 --> 01:05:57,086
You have two minutes.

1586
01:05:57,153 --> 01:05:58,688
You have under three minutes.

1587
01:05:58,754 --> 01:06:01,290
-Don't shake it.
-Don't shake it?

1588
01:06:01,357 --> 01:06:02,925
This may get burnt.

1589
01:06:02,992 --> 01:06:04,794
-Are you adding perilla leaves?
-Yes, as the topping.

1590
01:06:04,860 --> 01:06:07,330
That's the topping.
We're using perilla leaves a lot today.

1591
01:06:09,365 --> 01:06:11,067
He's adding lots of green onions again.

1592
01:06:11,133 --> 01:06:14,537
He added a lot.
I think he used about a dozen of them.

1593
01:06:14,603 --> 01:06:17,673
Jung-hwan, why don't you try
the buckwheat noodle soup?

1594
01:06:17,740 --> 01:06:21,310
He's stirring and stirring
with all of his effort.

1595
01:06:21,377 --> 01:06:23,079
-You have 2 minutes and 30 seconds.
-May I try it?

1596
01:06:23,145 --> 01:06:24,413
-Yes.
-Okay.

1597
01:06:24,480 --> 01:06:27,283
-You have 2 minutes and 30 seconds.
-What will it be like?

1598
01:06:27,350 --> 01:06:29,518
He put a lot of effort into that soup.

1599
01:06:30,286 --> 01:06:33,389
How's the soup?

1600
01:06:33,456 --> 01:06:37,193
WHAT'S THE SOUP LIKE
FOR D.P. BUCKWHEAT NOODLES?

1601
01:06:37,259 --> 01:06:38,260
How's the soup?

1602
01:06:38,327 --> 01:06:41,597
He won't have to take
his cap off next week.

1603
01:06:41,664 --> 01:06:43,265
FEELING PROUD

1604
01:06:43,332 --> 01:06:44,333
Whoa.

1605
01:06:44,400 --> 01:06:46,235
-It has that deep taste.
-It does?

1606
01:06:46,302 --> 01:06:47,603
-It does.
-Already?

1607
01:06:47,670 --> 01:06:50,740
As he mentioned before,
there's a hint of meaty taste.

1608
01:06:50,806 --> 01:06:54,110
-It has meaty taste?
-Yes, it also has that meat broth flavor.

1609
01:06:54,176 --> 01:06:55,411
Why? What did you put in?

1610
01:06:56,479 --> 01:06:58,014
Oh, it's meat…

1611
01:06:58,080 --> 01:07:01,217
-You have to work as you cook.
-Don't talk to him!

1612
01:07:01,283 --> 01:07:02,284
You have two minutes!

1613
01:07:02,351 --> 01:07:03,352
Two minutes!

1614
01:07:03,419 --> 01:07:05,921
Now, the pasta is
still uncooked over here.

1615
01:07:05,988 --> 01:07:07,456
Why don't you taste the pasta again?

1616
01:07:07,523 --> 01:07:09,358
-The pasta?
-How far has he come now?

1617
01:07:09,425 --> 01:07:11,160
Poong is losing his mind right now.

1618
01:07:11,227 --> 01:07:14,230
I've been curious
because the pasta wasn't cooked.

1619
01:07:14,296 --> 01:07:16,432
-Yes.
-Let me try some.

1620
01:07:16,499 --> 01:07:18,234
You have 1 minute and 30 seconds.

1621
01:07:19,001 --> 01:07:20,503
I think it's done.

1622
01:07:20,569 --> 01:07:22,805
I'll use the UNICHEF. Come out.

1623
01:07:22,872 --> 01:07:24,540
The UNICHEF.

1624
01:07:25,107 --> 01:07:27,543
Oh, it's now about al dente.

1625
01:07:27,610 --> 01:07:29,078
It's about al dente!

1626
01:07:29,145 --> 01:07:30,546
-Kwon Sung-jun.
-A minute and 30 seconds!

1627
01:07:30,613 --> 01:07:31,614
Chef Sung-jun is the UNICHEF.

1628
01:07:31,680 --> 01:07:33,115
Hey, wait.

1629
01:07:33,182 --> 01:07:34,917
The wheat… I can taste something.

1630
01:07:37,086 --> 01:07:40,322
I can taste a lot of wheat as I chew.

1631
01:07:40,389 --> 01:07:43,092
-Does it taste like wheat?
-This needs to be cooked more.

1632
01:07:43,159 --> 01:07:44,860
How will Chef Sung-jun help?

1633
01:07:44,927 --> 01:07:47,663
-It tastes like wheat?
-It tastes too much like wheat.

1634
01:07:47,730 --> 01:07:49,732
He's overseeing everything.

1635
01:07:50,299 --> 01:07:52,668
CHOI KANG-ROK PULLS OUT HIS PLATE

1636
01:07:53,302 --> 01:07:56,639
THE NOODLES GO
INTO THE BOWL FIRST

1637
01:07:57,206 --> 01:08:01,210
12. ADD NOODLES TO THE BOWL,
DROP EGGS INTO THE SOUP

1638
01:08:02,511 --> 01:08:04,747
Chef Sung-jun,

1639
01:08:04,814 --> 01:08:06,649
you should try it.

1640
01:08:06,715 --> 01:08:07,817
You have 30 seconds.

1641
01:08:07,883 --> 01:08:09,919
-It's fine.
-It's fine?

1642
01:08:09,985 --> 01:08:12,688
-It'll get cooked if he eats it after his.
-I see.

1643
01:08:12,755 --> 01:08:14,824
-You have to season it some more.
-Season it?

1644
01:08:14,890 --> 01:08:16,592
-It's a little bland, right?
-The sauce.

1645
01:08:16,659 --> 01:08:18,594
Can you put that in?

1646
01:08:18,661 --> 01:08:21,730
-Wait, Chef Sung-jun is cooking.
-Exactly.

1647
01:08:21,797 --> 01:08:23,566
-They're a team.
-This is cheating!

1648
01:08:23,632 --> 01:08:26,402
-It's the UNICHEF perk.
-He's doing everything!

1649
01:08:27,036 --> 01:08:28,471
Is that how you use the UNICHEF perk?

1650
01:08:28,537 --> 01:08:29,638
-Ten seconds.
-Ten.

1651
01:08:29,705 --> 01:08:31,874
-Nine. Eight.
-Just season it some more.

1652
01:08:31,941 --> 01:08:34,076
-Seven. Six.
-Forty seconds.

1653
01:08:34,143 --> 01:08:36,378
-Seven. Six.
-My time is up.

1654
01:08:36,445 --> 01:08:37,680
Five. Four.

1655
01:08:37,746 --> 01:08:39,381
Goodness, why?

1656
01:08:39,448 --> 01:08:42,384
-Five. Four. Three.
-No, I have no time.

1657
01:08:42,451 --> 01:08:45,888
-No.
-No, I have no time.

1658
01:08:45,955 --> 01:08:47,857
You still have 30 seconds.

1659
01:08:47,923 --> 01:08:50,893
-Five. Four. Three.
-No.

1660
01:08:50,960 --> 01:08:52,862
-Two. One.
-You still have thirty seconds.

1661
01:08:52,928 --> 01:08:54,930
-That was Chef Sung-jun.
-You aren't done yet.

1662
01:08:54,997 --> 01:08:56,999
Chef Sung-jun told him to use more time,

1663
01:08:57,066 --> 01:08:58,901
-but he just served it.
-Yes.

1664
01:08:58,968 --> 01:09:01,504
-What? I have more time?
-You have 20 seconds.

1665
01:09:01,570 --> 01:09:02,571
You do.

1666
01:09:02,638 --> 01:09:04,773
-You have 20 seconds.
-You still have time.

1667
01:09:05,708 --> 01:09:08,310
KANG-ROK JUST NEEDS
TO POUR THE SOUP

1668
01:09:08,811 --> 01:09:11,780
13. POUR SOUP OVER THE NOODLES

1669
01:09:12,848 --> 01:09:14,350
You have 20 seconds.

1670
01:09:14,416 --> 01:09:15,784
-No.
-What are you doing?

1671
01:09:15,851 --> 01:09:18,053
You have 20 seconds.

1672
01:09:18,120 --> 01:09:20,322
-No, don't do that.
-No, wait.

1673
01:09:20,389 --> 01:09:21,891
You have 20 seconds.

1674
01:09:21,957 --> 01:09:23,192
HE TAKES THE PLATE OVER THE HEAT?

1675
01:09:23,759 --> 01:09:26,262
THIS IS CHAOS

1676
01:09:26,328 --> 01:09:28,230
I've never seen anything like that.

1677
01:09:28,297 --> 01:09:29,431
STANDING OVATION

1678
01:09:29,498 --> 01:09:31,433
Just serve it.

1679
01:09:32,167 --> 01:09:34,069
You have 20 seconds!

1680
01:09:34,136 --> 01:09:36,038
Why didn't you tell me sooner?

1681
01:09:36,105 --> 01:09:38,207
We were counting for the UNICHEF.

1682
01:09:38,274 --> 01:09:41,176
-Ten. Nine. Eight.
-Ten. Nine. Eight.

1683
01:09:41,243 --> 01:09:43,312
-Seven. Six.
-Seven. Six.

1684
01:09:43,379 --> 01:09:46,115
-Five. Four. Three.
-Five. Four. Three.

1685
01:09:46,182 --> 01:09:49,251
-Five. Four. Three.
-No, wait.

1686
01:09:49,318 --> 01:09:51,954
-Two.
-Two. Chef Kang-rok is done.

1687
01:09:52,021 --> 01:09:53,422
Kim Poong is done too.

1688
01:09:56,525 --> 01:09:57,526
-My gosh.
-He put the dish…

1689
01:09:57,593 --> 01:10:00,763
He tried to put the plate over the heat.

1690
01:10:00,829 --> 01:10:02,531
-Goodness.
-That counting was for UNICHEF.

1691
01:10:02,598 --> 01:10:04,433
You can't put the dish over the heat.

1692
01:10:04,500 --> 01:10:07,570
When you counted down from ten,
it seemed like the end.

1693
01:10:07,636 --> 01:10:09,772
I was counting down for Chef Sung-jun.

1694
01:10:09,838 --> 01:10:12,841
-My gosh.
-Why did you wait until the end to use it?

1695
01:10:12,908 --> 01:10:14,677
You had about 30 more seconds.

1696
01:10:14,743 --> 01:10:16,979
-Good grief.
-He did.

1697
01:10:17,046 --> 01:10:18,681
Chef Kang-rok benefitted from this.

1698
01:10:18,747 --> 01:10:22,384
-Will the pasta get cooked over time?
-It will.

1699
01:10:22,451 --> 01:10:24,920
-Really?
-Yes, it's pretty wet.

1700
01:10:24,987 --> 01:10:29,225
And now, the dishes
for Bong-sik were all finished.

1701
01:10:29,291 --> 01:10:32,695
The noodles round was very chaotic.

1702
01:10:32,761 --> 01:10:35,531
First, you'll try Chef Kang-rok's dish.

1703
01:10:36,131 --> 01:10:39,568
FRIED SHRIMP WITH THE FLAVOR
OF DRIED LAVER FLAKES

1704
01:10:40,302 --> 01:10:43,472
AND MILKY SOUP
MADE WITH GREEN ONION

1705
01:10:44,607 --> 01:10:48,077
CHEF CHOI KANG-ROK'S
D.P. BUCKWHEAT NOODLES

1706
01:10:48,143 --> 01:10:51,313
You're about to eat
D.P. Buckwheat Noodles.

1707
01:10:52,314 --> 01:10:53,382
SNIFF

1708
01:10:53,449 --> 01:10:55,684
-It smells good.
-It does.

1709
01:10:55,751 --> 01:10:57,152
I'm so curious.

1710
01:10:57,219 --> 01:11:01,457
And adding the dried laver flakes
to the batter was a good touch.

1711
01:11:01,523 --> 01:11:02,691
He tries the shrimp first.

1712
01:11:03,359 --> 01:11:05,561
-It sounds crunchy.
-Yes.

1713
01:11:06,495 --> 01:11:10,032
He doesn't show any changes
while he eats his food.

1714
01:11:10,099 --> 01:11:11,300
Hmm?

1715
01:11:11,367 --> 01:11:12,668
-It's a bit…
-A bit?

1716
01:11:12,735 --> 01:11:14,770
I like the texture.

1717
01:11:14,837 --> 01:11:16,905
-But it tastes too bland.
-The fried shrimp?

1718
01:11:16,972 --> 01:11:19,074
-It tastes too bland.
-It tastes too bland.

1719
01:11:19,141 --> 01:11:21,644
He should've seasoned the batter.

1720
01:11:21,710 --> 01:11:24,046
You were supposed to dip it in the soup.

1721
01:11:24,113 --> 01:11:25,581
He has to dip it in the soup.

1722
01:11:25,648 --> 01:11:29,718
He's supposed to soak it in.
It needs the sauce on the fry.

1723
01:11:29,785 --> 01:11:33,555
I see. That must mean
the soup is rather salty.

1724
01:11:33,622 --> 01:11:35,257
WILL IT TASTE ALL RIGHT?

1725
01:11:35,324 --> 01:11:36,592
Was that okay?

1726
01:11:36,659 --> 01:11:37,760
Mmm.

1727
01:11:38,727 --> 01:11:39,728
Does it taste right?

1728
01:11:39,795 --> 01:11:41,997
-Yes, it's different.
-It's different.

1729
01:11:42,064 --> 01:11:43,465
He had to eat it with the soup.

1730
01:11:43,532 --> 01:11:45,668
-You should've told him.
-Right.

1731
01:11:45,734 --> 01:11:48,437
I'm sorry. I should've asked.

1732
01:11:48,504 --> 01:11:50,306
He said he should've asked.

1733
01:11:50,372 --> 01:11:51,807
HE SIPS THE GREEN ONION SOUP

1734
01:11:52,308 --> 01:11:53,309
YUM

1735
01:11:53,375 --> 01:11:56,178
He tries the soup first,
and he works on the noodles.

1736
01:11:57,179 --> 01:11:58,480
Whoa.

1737
01:11:58,547 --> 01:12:00,382
Whoa, isn't it hot?

1738
01:12:00,449 --> 01:12:01,617
The noodles.

1739
01:12:02,785 --> 01:12:05,354
-It must be hot.
-I guess he's fine.

1740
01:12:05,421 --> 01:12:08,424
Are you putting up with it,
even though it's too hot?

1741
01:12:08,490 --> 01:12:10,626
Hot noodles taste the best
when it's hot, though.

1742
01:12:11,527 --> 01:12:12,795
It tastes very healthy.

1743
01:12:12,861 --> 01:12:14,930
-I see.
-A healthy taste.

1744
01:12:15,564 --> 01:12:17,466
-That expression…
-This isn't good.

1745
01:12:17,533 --> 01:12:19,635
…can both mean good and bad.

1746
01:12:19,702 --> 01:12:21,503
You can't win if it tastes healthy.

1747
01:12:21,570 --> 01:12:23,305
CHUCKLING

1748
01:12:24,106 --> 01:12:28,911
Maybe he means he can eat a lot
because it tastes healthy.

1749
01:12:29,478 --> 01:12:31,814
-The green onion flavor.
-Fills his mouth.

1750
01:12:31,880 --> 01:12:33,716
The green onion flavor.
He used a lot of green onions.

1751
01:12:33,782 --> 01:12:35,451
-He must've used a dozen.
-Yes.

1752
01:12:35,517 --> 01:12:38,554
He made all three UNICHEFs
work on the green onion.

1753
01:12:38,620 --> 01:12:40,622
It tastes refreshing because of that,

1754
01:12:40,689 --> 01:12:42,691
but it's also thick too.

1755
01:12:42,758 --> 01:12:45,661
It must taste like <i>ulmyeon</i>
in Korean-Chinese cuisine.

1756
01:12:45,728 --> 01:12:47,463
-It's like that.
-Yes, it is.

1757
01:12:47,529 --> 01:12:48,597
That's the thickness.

1758
01:12:48,664 --> 01:12:50,733
Does the soup taste meaty?

1759
01:12:50,799 --> 01:12:53,569
-There's a hint of it.
-A hint of it.

1760
01:12:53,635 --> 01:12:57,606
It would've tasted too much
like vegetable with just green onion,

1761
01:12:57,673 --> 01:13:01,577
so I added some butter
to add that savory taste.

1762
01:13:01,643 --> 01:13:03,712
Butter. That was a good tip.

1763
01:13:03,779 --> 01:13:06,348
He added some depth to the flavor.

1764
01:13:06,415 --> 01:13:09,585
It may taste too plain at first,

1765
01:13:09,651 --> 01:13:13,555
-but you'll keep going back for more.
-It's like <i>ulmyeon</i>.

1766
01:13:13,622 --> 01:13:15,691
-I see. Good.
-Like <i>ulmyeon</i>.

1767
01:13:16,625 --> 01:13:19,928
CHINESE-STYLE PASTA
TOPPED WITH PERILLA LEAVES

1768
01:13:21,430 --> 01:13:25,401
THE PASTA NOODLES
KWON SUNG-JUN RESUSCITATED

1769
01:13:26,835 --> 01:13:30,439
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
NAPOLI POONGFIA

1770
01:13:30,506 --> 01:13:32,307
-You can eat it.
-Mix it well.

1771
01:13:32,374 --> 01:13:33,942
Bong-sik, may I try that?

1772
01:13:34,009 --> 01:13:35,444
-What?
-This one?

1773
01:13:35,511 --> 01:13:37,312
-Yes, this one.
-He was curious.

1774
01:13:37,379 --> 01:13:40,082
Suk-ku is getting curious.

1775
01:13:41,250 --> 01:13:42,818
-Let's share.
-Okay.

1776
01:13:42,885 --> 01:13:45,220
Wait, Kyun.

1777
01:13:45,287 --> 01:13:47,423
-I'm hungry.
-You love to eat. You're hungry?

1778
01:13:47,489 --> 01:13:50,993
HE COULDN'T HOLD BACK
AND QUICKLY GETS A TASTE

1779
01:13:51,627 --> 01:13:53,595
-Do you like <i>ulmyeon</i>?
-Yes.

1780
01:13:54,096 --> 01:13:56,832
-It looks good.
-I think it's fully cooked.

1781
01:13:56,899 --> 01:13:58,033
-It is.
-I see.

1782
01:13:58,100 --> 01:14:01,003
That was left here for a while,
so it could've been fully cooked.

1783
01:14:01,069 --> 01:14:03,205
You can eat the pasta
with green onion and perilla leaves.

1784
01:14:03,772 --> 01:14:04,973
GETS PERILLA LEAVES

1785
01:14:05,040 --> 01:14:06,475
Green onion and perilla leaves.

1786
01:14:07,109 --> 01:14:08,710
INTO HIS MOUTH

1787
01:14:08,777 --> 01:14:10,312
Bong-sik took a bite.

1788
01:14:11,780 --> 01:14:14,149
-Chinese-style pasta.
-Pasta.

1789
01:14:14,216 --> 01:14:15,517
I wonder how it is.

1790
01:14:15,584 --> 01:14:17,753
The problem is if the pasta is cooked.

1791
01:14:17,820 --> 01:14:20,556
He had 30 more seconds,
but he served it anyway.

1792
01:14:20,622 --> 01:14:22,157
-The pasta is cooked.
-It is?

1793
01:14:22,224 --> 01:14:24,626
The pasta is cooked.

1794
01:14:24,693 --> 01:14:26,161
-That was unexpected.
-It looks good.

1795
01:14:26,228 --> 01:14:27,896
Is it spicy?

1796
01:14:27,963 --> 01:14:30,966
It wasn't as spicy as I thought.

1797
01:14:31,033 --> 01:14:33,635
The tacos were spicier for him.

1798
01:14:33,702 --> 01:14:36,572
He has a satisfying way
of eating these noodles.

1799
01:14:36,638 --> 01:14:39,808
I feel like we should be quiet
while he's taking a bite.

1800
01:14:39,875 --> 01:14:42,411
EVERYONE IS FOCUSED
ON BONG-SIK, BUT…

1801
01:14:44,012 --> 01:14:46,248
THESE TWO ARE
IN THEIR OWN LITTLE WORLD

1802
01:14:46,815 --> 01:14:47,816
THEY'RE SHARING THE NOODLES

1803
01:14:47,883 --> 01:14:49,718
The problem is if the pasta is cooked.

1804
01:14:50,319 --> 01:14:52,688
He had 30 more seconds,
but he served it anyway.

1805
01:14:53,255 --> 01:14:55,724
-This is good.
-The pasta is cooked.

1806
01:14:55,791 --> 01:14:57,125
LOOKING OVER

1807
01:14:57,192 --> 01:14:59,561
Wait, what are you two doing right now?

1808
01:14:59,628 --> 01:15:02,297
-We're on a date.
-A date?

1809
01:15:02,364 --> 01:15:05,567
-We won't bother you.
-No.

1810
01:15:06,201 --> 01:15:08,036
RUBBING

1811
01:15:08,103 --> 01:15:09,605
He's rubbing his back.

1812
01:15:09,671 --> 01:15:11,206
THEY LOOK GOOD TOGETHER

1813
01:15:11,273 --> 01:15:13,342
All right. That was great.

1814
01:15:13,408 --> 01:15:14,610
How was that, Suk-ku?

1815
01:15:14,676 --> 01:15:16,445
-It's so good.
-Is it?

1816
01:15:16,512 --> 01:15:19,915
It has a stronger taste than most <i>ulmyeon</i>.

1817
01:15:19,982 --> 01:15:22,184
-It's very delicious.
-He enjoyed it.

1818
01:15:22,251 --> 01:15:24,720
He's had lots of noodle dishes.

1819
01:15:24,786 --> 01:15:27,789
-He said he loved noodles.
-Yes, look at his spinning technique.

1820
01:15:27,856 --> 01:15:29,258
-It looks good.
-It must be.

1821
01:15:29,324 --> 01:15:31,560
Because we had to take his fridge here,

1822
01:15:31,627 --> 01:15:33,028
he probably couldn't have eaten well.

1823
01:15:33,095 --> 01:15:35,664
-Yes, we couldn't do anything about that.
-No.

1824
01:15:35,731 --> 01:15:38,500
The pasta would've been better
if it was cooked a bit more.

1825
01:15:38,567 --> 01:15:40,602
I see. You said it was done, though.

1826
01:15:40,669 --> 01:15:43,171
It was partially undercooked.

1827
01:15:43,238 --> 01:15:47,209
The ones on the inside are done,
but the ones on the outside aren't.

1828
01:15:47,276 --> 01:15:50,712
-I see. It wasn't cooked evenly.
-I see.

1829
01:15:50,779 --> 01:15:52,180
Gosh, the noodles.

1830
01:15:52,247 --> 01:15:54,583
It could've been cooked
with that bit of time.

1831
01:15:54,650 --> 01:15:58,053
It would've been cooked evenly
if you held out for 20 more seconds.

1832
01:15:58,120 --> 01:15:59,488
It wasn't cooked evenly.

1833
01:15:59,555 --> 01:16:03,125
Other than that, it tastes wonderful.

1834
01:16:03,191 --> 01:16:06,962
The flavor of the cabbage, green onion,
and perilla leaves

1835
01:16:07,029 --> 01:16:08,530
all mix together nicely.

1836
01:16:08,597 --> 01:16:12,401
It even tastes fresh.

1837
01:16:12,467 --> 01:16:13,835
I see.

1838
01:16:14,803 --> 01:16:17,272
Suk-ku, are you waiting for that?

1839
01:16:17,339 --> 01:16:18,774
-I've been waiting.
-Yes.

1840
01:16:18,840 --> 01:16:21,543
-He wants to eat it.
-He's lined up.

1841
01:16:21,610 --> 01:16:22,911
-It's still warm.
-Goodness.

1842
01:16:22,978 --> 01:16:23,979
Their date begins.

1843
01:16:24,580 --> 01:16:29,117
THE TWO EVEN EAT IN A SIMILAR WAY

1844
01:16:29,685 --> 01:16:31,386
Did you try the shrimp?

1845
01:16:31,453 --> 01:16:33,121
-I haven't.
-You should try some.

1846
01:16:33,188 --> 01:16:36,391
He's feeding him with his hand and all.

1847
01:16:36,458 --> 01:16:38,226
They've become very close.

1848
01:16:38,293 --> 01:16:39,695
Yes, we became very close.

1849
01:16:39,761 --> 01:16:42,130
-I told him that I was his fan too.
-You did?

1850
01:16:42,197 --> 01:16:46,268
I see.
Then why didn't you give him a star?

1851
01:16:46,335 --> 01:16:48,503
You didn't even give him a star.

1852
01:16:48,570 --> 01:16:50,339
-How was that one?
-How was it?

1853
01:16:50,405 --> 01:16:52,240
It tastes so good.

1854
01:16:52,307 --> 01:16:54,776
But the pasta was undercooked.

1855
01:16:54,843 --> 01:16:58,080
The pasta was a tad bit undercooked.

1856
01:16:58,146 --> 01:16:59,815
You won't eat this anymore.

1857
01:17:00,549 --> 01:17:02,484
I think I can guess this one too.

1858
01:17:03,051 --> 01:17:05,787
HE CAN PREDICT BONG-SIK'S CHOICE

1859
01:17:05,854 --> 01:17:07,489
-I see.
-Goodness.

1860
01:17:07,556 --> 01:17:09,691
-There may be a twist.
-Yes.

1861
01:17:09,758 --> 01:17:11,660
You never know what Bong-sik is thinking.

1862
01:17:11,727 --> 01:17:12,928
He may have his own style.

1863
01:17:12,995 --> 01:17:16,999
And now, it's time to make your choice.

1864
01:17:17,065 --> 01:17:18,600
Press one for Kim Poong.

1865
01:17:18,667 --> 01:17:20,669
Press two for Choi Kang-rok.

1866
01:17:20,736 --> 01:17:22,270
Make your decision.

1867
01:17:22,337 --> 01:17:24,506
And please press the button!

1868
01:17:24,573 --> 01:17:27,609
Both contestants have no stars.

1869
01:17:27,676 --> 01:17:31,546
He presses one button resolutely.

1870
01:17:31,613 --> 01:17:34,583
-Let us see the result.
-The result.

1871
01:17:34,650 --> 01:17:37,219
Who's going to take the star?

1872
01:17:37,285 --> 01:17:39,354
It's an important battle.

1873
01:17:39,421 --> 01:17:43,558
Who did Hyun Bong-sik choose?

1874
01:17:43,625 --> 01:17:46,662
Let's find out
who won the noodle dish round!

1875
01:17:46,728 --> 01:17:50,098
Noodle Bong-sik.

1876
01:17:50,165 --> 01:17:52,067
Was it Kim Poong's pasta?

1877
01:17:52,134 --> 01:17:54,236
Or was it
Choi Kang-rok's buckwheat noodles?

1878
01:17:54,302 --> 01:17:58,840
Who did Bong-sik choose?
Who won the significant first star?

1879
01:17:58,907 --> 01:18:00,208
Who is it?

1880
01:18:00,275 --> 01:18:02,844
Who did he choose?

1881
01:18:02,911 --> 01:18:04,946
Choi Kang-rok!

1882
01:18:05,013 --> 01:18:07,215
CHEF CHOI KANG-ROK'S
D.P. BUCKWHEAT NOODLES WINS

1883
01:18:07,282 --> 01:18:08,316
Choi Kang-rok wins!

1884
01:18:08,383 --> 01:18:10,752
-This is his first star!
-Yes!

1885
01:18:10,819 --> 01:18:13,288
Chef Kang-rok finally wins a star.

1886
01:18:13,355 --> 01:18:16,158
AND KIM POONG'S
4 CONSECUTIVE LOSSES…

1887
01:18:16,224 --> 01:18:18,660
Artist Poong's dish was

1888
01:18:18,727 --> 01:18:21,530
the kind of flavor I usually prefer.

1889
01:18:21,596 --> 01:18:25,200
-But the pasta was undercooked.
-That was a significant flaw.

1890
01:18:25,267 --> 01:18:29,438
Why did you get confused
with the 30 seconds? I'm feeling bad now.

1891
01:18:29,504 --> 01:18:30,772
IF ONLY HE DIDN'T GET
THAT CONFUSED…

1892
01:18:30,839 --> 01:18:33,642
Artist Poong
fails to cook his noodles fully,

1893
01:18:33,709 --> 01:18:36,978
so the first star goes to Chef Kang-rok.

1894
01:18:37,045 --> 01:18:38,313
It's his first star.

1895
01:18:38,380 --> 01:18:41,183
Please put a star on him, Bong-sik!

1896
01:18:41,249 --> 01:18:44,152
Chef Kang-rok receives his first star!

1897
01:18:44,219 --> 01:18:45,320
Congratulations!

1898
01:18:46,254 --> 01:18:47,823
The first star from Bong-sik.

1899
01:18:48,924 --> 01:18:50,492
Great work today.

1900
01:18:50,559 --> 01:18:52,661
-Great job.
-Gosh, thank you.

1901
01:18:52,728 --> 01:18:54,830
Anyway, congratulations.

1902
01:18:54,896 --> 01:18:57,199
THEY NEED A CUP OF ICED WATER
AFTER A TUMULTUOUS BATTLE

1903
01:18:57,265 --> 01:18:59,034
And grated ice.

1904
01:18:59,101 --> 01:19:01,737
YOU CAN HAVE ANY KIND
OF ICE YOU LIKE

1905
01:19:02,471 --> 01:19:04,539
There are different kinds of ice.

1906
01:19:06,208 --> 01:19:09,211
It's made with clean water,
so you can feel free to have some.

1907
01:19:10,345 --> 01:19:12,547
STAY TUNED FOR NEXT WEEK'S
FRIDGE OWNERS,

1908
01:19:12,614 --> 01:19:14,082
HA JI-WON AND JANG KEUN-SUK

1909
01:19:14,149 --> 01:19:15,217
-It's cold.
-Yes.

1910
01:19:15,283 --> 01:19:16,952
Today's fridge owners!

1911
01:19:17,018 --> 01:19:19,821
Please welcome
Ha Ji-won and Jang Keun-suk!

1912
01:19:19,888 --> 01:19:21,590
He was my first love

1913
01:19:21,656 --> 01:19:24,459
-back when we were in <i>Hwang Jini</i>.
-Yes, it's been 19 years.

1914
01:19:24,526 --> 01:19:25,961
I said I wanted to be on this episode.

1915
01:19:26,027 --> 01:19:28,430
-May I have an autograph?
-Goodness.

1916
01:19:28,497 --> 01:19:29,564
I study people's eyes.

1917
01:19:29,631 --> 01:19:31,767
What about Ji-won's eyes?

1918
01:19:31,833 --> 01:19:34,269
-He took a quick peek.
-You have to look at her.

1919
01:19:34,336 --> 01:19:36,004
What do you have to eat
not to age like you?

1920
01:19:36,071 --> 01:19:37,973
-That's my secret.
-This?

1921
01:19:38,039 --> 01:19:40,308
I put it in olive oil.

1922
01:19:40,375 --> 01:19:43,078
-With rice?
-And into ramyeon, I put in…

1923
01:19:43,145 --> 01:19:44,012
-What?
-What?

1924
01:19:44,079 --> 01:19:46,548
-Can we try that?
-It's rationed.

1925
01:19:46,615 --> 01:19:47,883
WHAT'S JI-WON'S SECRET
TO LOOKING YOUNG?

1926
01:19:47,949 --> 01:19:49,284
In the previous season,

1927
01:19:49,351 --> 01:19:50,585
he had eight wins and eight losses.

1928
01:19:50,652 --> 01:19:51,653
It's the Sam-Poong derby.

1929
01:19:51,720 --> 01:19:53,288
<i>I'll start rising up now.</i>

1930
01:19:53,355 --> 01:19:55,223
What are you doing at his counter?

1931
01:19:55,290 --> 01:19:57,025
Let me use some of these.

1932
01:19:57,092 --> 01:19:59,594
<i>Poong looks high-spirited.</i>

1933
01:19:59,661 --> 01:20:01,930
<i>Welcome. It's your first time</i>
<i>on</i> Chef & My Fridge, <i>right?</i>

1934
01:20:01,997 --> 01:20:04,366
<i>I'll fight Kang-rok</i>
<i>and win twice in a row.</i>

1935
01:20:04,432 --> 01:20:05,433
Where's the lid?

1936
01:20:05,500 --> 01:20:06,735
It's right here.

1937
01:20:06,802 --> 01:20:08,003
Why won't this come out?

1938
01:20:08,069 --> 01:20:09,171
MR. SLOW VS MR. ANXIETY

1939
01:20:09,237 --> 01:20:11,439
-Sugar.
-Oh, no.

1940
01:20:12,174 --> 01:20:14,209
You have 1 minute and 25 seconds!

1941
01:20:14,276 --> 01:20:15,811
-Yes.
-Does it taste like medicine?

1942
01:20:15,877 --> 01:20:17,479
It's like a sauna!

1943
01:20:17,546 --> 01:20:18,980
<i>It does, doesn't it?</i>

1944
01:20:19,047 --> 01:20:20,248
<i>It feels like sauna!</i>

1945
01:20:20,315 --> 01:20:22,083
It's Gil Ra-im.

1946
01:20:22,717 --> 01:20:23,819
What are you talking about?

1947
01:20:33,228 --> 01:20:38,233
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
